(* Beginning of Notebook Content *)
Notebook[{
Cell["2-D Barotropic Vorticity on a Rotating Sphere", "Title",ExpressionUUID->"ec41673b-6ddd-4dd4-823d-4f380bb29684"],

Cell["\<\
A spectral 2-D turbulence model \[Dash] motivated by, but not a model of, \
solar convection\
\>", "Subtitle",ExpressionUUID->"0f09935b-fa91-4f09-b774-cccae98131b7"],

Cell["\<\
This notebook accompanies the Python simulation simulate_v6.py, which solves \
the 2-D barotropic vorticity equation on a rotating sphere with a \
spherical-harmonic (spectral) method. Be clear at the outset about what it is \
and what it is not. It is NOT a convection model: it has no buoyancy, no \
energy (temperature) equation, no vertical velocity, and no radial dimension. \
What it shares with solar convection is only the rotating-sphere geometry and \
the kinematics of forced two-dimensional turbulence. Solar convection appears \
in this notebook as motivation and as the source of that geometry; the \
dynamics the model actually solves are those of a single scalar vorticity \
field, stirred by a stochastic forcing that stands in \[Dash] kinematically, \
not physically \[Dash] for the stirring that convection would provide. Read \
as a self-contained tutorial: the motivating physics of solar convection, the \
mathematics of barotropic vorticity on a rotating sphere, the relevant \
dimensionless numbers, the numerics of the spectral solver, and the geometry \
behind the 3-D cutaway visualisation. Every code cell is standalone \[Dash] \
evaluate them in any order.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f90bbf2a-a2e4-4567-ae69-e49bf9a5eef7"],

Cell["\<\
Colour convention throughout: red = cyclonic (positive vertical vorticity), \
blue = anticyclonic (negative), white = zero \[Dash] the same diverging map \
(TemperatureMap) used by the simulation's renderer.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9bed34f4-24c7-4011-bedf-bd5e333a7a51"],

Cell["1.  Solar Convection \[LongDash] Physical Background", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"654b2654-f132-4a06-b0ec-09098f10af69"],

Cell["\<\
The Sun is a ball of plasma about 700,000 km in radius. Energy generated by \
hydrogen fusion in the core must escape to the surface, and it does so in two \
very different ways depending on depth. Below roughly 0.71 solar radii the \
plasma is optically thick but stable to overturning: energy diffuses outward \
as radiation (the radiative zone). Above 0.71 solar radii the temperature \
gradient becomes steep enough that the plasma is convectively unstable \
\[Dash] hot fluid rises, cools, and sinks in a churning, turbulent layer: the \
convection zone.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3dd12690-b7c2-4259-b2c1-5dab2e74ac83"],

Cell["1.1  Why solar convection matters", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"ed06139a-d34c-4399-99b5-57a74b268381"],

Cell["\<\
Convection is not a cosmetic surface feature; it is the engine of solar \
magnetism and variability:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d15324d1-a62f-4caf-bed9-d43b8b6e4b30"],

Cell["\<\
It transports the entire solar luminosity (\[TildeTilde] \
3.8\[Times]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(10\), \(26\)]\) W) across the outer third \
of the Sun by radius.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"846d4645-2694-4841-830f-d848f35b5b86"],

Cell["\<\
Its interaction with rotation sustains the Sun's differential rotation \
\[Dash] the equator rotates in about 25 days, the poles in about 35.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"ded7ff63-027c-4e71-a88b-b840bf4bcb52"],

Cell["\<\
Rotating, electrically conducting convection drives the solar dynamo, \
producing the 11-year sunspot cycle and the magnetic activity that governs \
space weather.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"7bca7652-9c41-4e30-8cdf-5fc9ea857a44"],

Cell["\<\
The granulation and supergranulation patterns seen on the photosphere are the \
visible tops of convective cells.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"20107fc9-1ef9-44b0-ba53-7a59f1c6a7e6"],

Cell["1.2  The three key ingredients", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"b017ba07-b44e-4427-a5d7-14894ee8847d"],

Cell["\<\
Real solar convection is driven by buoyancy, shaped by rotation, and \[Dash] \
in the rapidly rotating limit \[Dash] constrained by the \
Taylor\[Dash]Proudman theorem. It is worth naming these three ingredients to \
set the scene, but note carefully, in advance, which of them the 2-D \
barotropic model actually contains. Only one of the three (rotation) is \
present.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"68787d25-1a90-4449-9c20-47cab08dd816"],

Cell["\<\
Buoyancy \[Dash] NOT in this model. In real convection, density variations \
multiplied by gravity produce a buoyancy force: warm fluid is lighter and \
rises, cool fluid sinks. That force is what drives convection and selects its \
scales. The barotropic model has no temperature field, no energy equation, \
and no vertical velocity, so it contains no buoyancy whatsoever. In its place \
a stochastic forcing simply injects vorticity at chosen scales \[Dash] the \
flow is stirred, not driven, and the \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]convective\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] scale is imposed by hand rather than selected by an \
instability.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"cc12c62a-ac38-4818-b557-dbf3aab1aece"],

Cell["\<\
Rotation \[Dash] the one ingredient this model DOES keep. The Sun rotates, so \
the fluid feels the Coriolis force. In a 2-D model rotation enters through a \
single mechanism: the advection of planetary vorticity f = 2\[CapitalOmega] \
sin\[Phi], i.e. the \[Beta]-effect (Section 2.3). On the large scales \
relevant here, rotation is the single most important organising influence \
\[Dash] far stronger, dynamically, than viscosity.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3ab5bde1-e5b7-447e-b7fb-6bb2793f47ef"],

Cell["\<\
The Taylor\[Dash]Proudman constraint \[Dash] NOT in this model. In a rapidly \
rotating fluid the flow tends to become invariant ALONG the rotation axis, \
organising convection into tall columns (\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]banana cells\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]) aligned with the axis rather than isotropic blobs. \
This is an intrinsically THREE-dimensional balance \[Dash] it constrains \
variation along the axis, a direction a 2-D surface model does not even \
possess. We derive it in Section 3 as motivating background, but a 2-D \
barotropic model cannot produce banana cells by this mechanism; any \
axis-aligned striping it shows is a property of individual spherical \
harmonics, not the signature of rotationally constrained convection.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ba0ed27c-c4b9-4795-bf81-44796ff32a1d"],

Cell["1.3  A schematic of the solar interior", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"3fd535f3-326a-4d8c-8abf-be6d6302900e"],

Cell["\<\
The cell below draws a labelled cross-section of the Sun's interior \
structure: the fusion core, the radiative zone, the thin tachocline shear \
layer at its top, and the turbulent convection zone reaching to the \
photosphere. Radii are in units of the solar radius \!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(R\), \
\(\[CircleDot]\)]\).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f7ba7eb7-cd0b-4350-b05f-f31a9501253f"],

Cell["\<\
Module[{rCore = 0.25, rRad = 0.71, rSun = 1.0,
  granule, spokes},
 (* a little photospheric granulation on the rim *)
 granule = Table[
   {Hue[0.09, 0.55, 1], Disk[0.965 {Cos[a], Sin[a]}, 0.028]},
   {a, 0, 2 Pi - 0.01, 2 Pi/44}];
 Graphics[{
   (* convection zone *)
   {Hue[0.07, 0.75, 1.0], Disk[{0, 0}, rSun]},
   (* radiative zone *)
   {Hue[0.12, 0.65, 1.0], Disk[{0, 0}, rRad]},
   (* tachocline: thin shear layer at 0.71 R *)
   {Directive[Red, Opacity[0.55], Thickness[0.006]], Circle[{0, 0}, rRad]},
   (* fusion core *)
   {Hue[0.02, 0.85, 1.0], Disk[{0, 0}, rCore]},
   granule,
   (* convective rolls (schematic) *)
   {GrayLevel[0.25], Thickness[0.002],
    Table[Circle[(0.855) {Cos[a], Sin[a]}, 0.085, {0, Pi}],
     {a, Pi/10, 2 Pi, 2 Pi/16}]},
   (* labels *)
   Black, Thick,
   Text[Style[\"Core\\n(fusion)\", 12, White, Bold], {0, 0}],
   Text[Style[\"Radiative zone\", 12, Black, Bold], {0, 0.48}],
   Text[Style[\"Convection zone\", 12, Black, Bold], {0, 0.855}],
   {Red, Text[Style[\"tachocline (0.71 R)\", 9, Bold], {0.42, -0.62}]},
   Arrow[{{0.30, -0.60}, {0.50 Cos[-3 Pi/4] + 0.05, 0.71 Sin[-3 Pi/4]/1.0 - \
0.0}}]
   },
  PlotRange -> 1.15 {{-1, 1}, {-1, 1}}, ImageSize -> 460,
  PlotLabel -> Style[\"Interior structure of the Sun\", 14, Bold]]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"dd0b1b45-2270-4f58-9970-79e6b9c9dfe3"],

Cell["\<\
The convective envelope occupies only the outer 29% of the Sun by radius but, \
because of the geometry, a substantial fraction of its volume. Our simulation \
models the dynamics on a representative spherical surface within this \
envelope.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fca9e1a7-fea4-49c2-883e-481d8f555b76"],

Cell["2.  The Mathematics", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"759eff0b-33a7-4cc7-82a7-d0fbf8f7225e"],

Cell["\<\
The full problem \[Dash] compressible, magnetised, rotating convection in a \
stratified sphere \[Dash] is formidable. The barotropic vorticity equation is \
the simplest model that still captures the essence of rotation-dominated, \
quasi-two-dimensional turbulence on a sphere. It describes the evolution of a \
single scalar field, the vertical (radial) vorticity, on a spherical surface.\
\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"339fbb86-10ba-48a9-9e19-564125b55434"],

Cell["2.1  From momentum to vorticity", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"b46de348-1e83-48f3-8ba2-590070e2cc4f"],

Cell["\<\
Start from the momentum equation for a thin, incompressible fluid layer on a \
rotating sphere. Horizontal velocity \!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(\
\[RightVector]\)]\) obeys\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fced6844-7ecc-4639-9611-266359984098"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox["\[PartialD]", 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], 
   OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "+", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", "\[Del]"}], ")"}], 
    OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], "+", 
   RowBox[{"f", " ", 
    OverscriptBox["z", "^"], "\[Cross]", 
    OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    FractionBox["1", "\[Rho]"], 
    RowBox[{"\[Del]", "p"}]}], "+", 
   OverscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalF]", "\[RightVector]"]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"5b58eb25-b700-4e3a-94c6-19ec923cb876"],

Cell["\<\
Here f = 2\[CapitalOmega] sin\[Phi] is the Coriolis parameter \
(\[CapitalOmega] the rotation rate, \[Phi] latitude) and \!\(\*OverscriptBox[\
\(\[ScriptCapitalF]\), \(\[RightVector]\)]\) collects friction and forcing. \
Taking the vertical component of the curl, \!\(\*RowBox[{OverscriptBox[\(z\), \
\(^\)], \(\[CenterDot]\), \(\[Del]\[Cross] \((\[CenterDot])\)\)}]\), and \
using incompressibility (\[Del]\[CenterDot]\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(\
\[RightVector]\)]\) = 0) eliminates the pressure term entirely and yields the \
evolution of the relative vertical vorticity \[Omega] = \
\!\(\*RowBox[{OverscriptBox[\(z\), \(^\)], \(\[CenterDot]\), RowBox[{\(\[Del]\
\[Cross]\), OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(\[RightVector]\)]}]}]\):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f6d6bdb4-6632-4655-97fe-51f42c084b66"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Omega]"}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
   RowBox[{"J", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ",", " ", "\[Omega]", "+", "f"}], ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", "\[Nu]", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"-", 
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"]}], ")"}], "4"], "\[Omega]"}], "-", 
   RowBox[{"\[Mu]", " ", "\[Omega]"}], "+", "F"}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"1e705214-7a6b-40eb-bdde-8586f440bd09"],

Cell["\<\
This is the equation the simulation integrates. Reading the terms left to \
right:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f8b3ff9c-74ba-4a0b-a456-b43533aee9d0"],

Cell["\[PartialD]\[Omega]/\[PartialD]t \[Dash] local rate of change of \
vorticity.", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"ec172d64-b5c4-4d3a-9ab3-f35dcd5418f2"],

Cell["\<\
J(\[Psi], \[Omega]+f) \[Dash] nonlinear advection of absolute vorticity by \
the flow (the Jacobian, defined below). This is the term that makes the \
problem turbulent.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"834efd5d-32cd-486c-bc98-80c0f440a9fc"],

Cell["\<\
-\[Nu] \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\((-\[Del]\[Cross]\[Del])\), \(4\)]\)\[Omega] \
\[Dash] \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[Del]\), \(8\)]\) hyperviscosity, a \
scale-selective drain that only removes the very smallest scales (Section 4).\
\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"491cbb35-de53-4323-afed-fea0f253deb5"],

Cell["\<\
-\[Mu] \[Omega] \[Dash] uniform linear (Rayleigh) drag that removes energy \
from the largest scales so the turbulence reaches a statistically steady \
state.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"a36314ce-9cf6-4f7c-b29e-3c8a342d15ee"],

Cell["\<\
F \[Dash] stochastic (white-in-time) forcing that injects vorticity in a \
chosen band of scales. It is an imposed stirring, a kinematic stand-in for \
the stirring convective plumes would provide; it is NOT buoyancy and does not \
arise from any instability. The forced scale is put in by hand through the \
forcing band, not selected by the dynamics.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"fe5a4fa1-2fd4-4161-a0cf-34f52d389a17"],

Cell["\<\
2.2  Streamfunction and the vorticity\[Dash]streamfunction relation\
\>", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"22d5e337-5311-43aa-af2a-c2d624bbeee7"],

Cell["\<\
Because the horizontal flow is non-divergent, it can be written in terms of a \
single scalar streamfunction \[Psi]. Velocity is the skew-gradient of \[Psi], \
and vorticity is its Laplacian:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"bfaecef9-ca3b-4286-b99e-6d5e2ea7b1a6"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"\[Omega]", "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "\[Psi]"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"419dd35f-88fb-4b8f-8fe7-d3d54a9a6c2c"],

Cell["\<\
Inverting this relation \[Dash] recovering \[Psi] from \[Omega] \[Dash] is a \
Poisson problem, \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[Del]\), \(2\)]\)\[Psi] = \[Omega]. \
On the sphere it is trivial in spectral space, as we will see, because \
spherical harmonics diagonalise the Laplacian.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a9b43a2c-048e-4e90-bdc1-14ed85733615"],

Cell["2.3  The Coriolis parameter and planetary vorticity", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"a79d90b0-80cc-47f9-81f1-8a46ce7713b7"],

Cell["\<\
The background planetary vorticity \[Dash] the vorticity of the solid-body \
rotation of the sphere itself \[Dash] is f = 2\[CapitalOmega] sin\[Phi]. It \
vanishes at the equator and is largest at the poles:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a473f180-48f5-4523-9147-3db4583c73a8"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"f", "=", 
   RowBox[{"2", " ", "\[CapitalOmega]", " ", "sin", "\[Phi]"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"76373e20-743a-4faa-9c6f-23b5a7fd92e0"],

Cell["\<\
Its gradient, the famous \[Beta] = df/dy, is the restoring mechanism for \
Rossby waves and the reason large-scale geophysical turbulence is \
anisotropic. In the spectral code, f is exactly a single spherical-harmonic \
mode: since \!\(\*SubsuperscriptBox[\(Y\), \(1\), \(0\)]\) \[Proportional] \
sin\[Phi], the field 2\[CapitalOmega] sin\[Phi] is proportional to \
\!\(\*SubsuperscriptBox[\(Y\), \(1\), \(0\)]\) alone \[Dash] which is exactly \
how simulate_v6.py stores it. But \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]proportional to \!\(\
\*SubsuperscriptBox[\(Y\), \(1\), \(0\)]\)\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] hides a \
constant whose value depends entirely on the harmonic normalisation \[Dash] \
and getting that constant wrong is exactly the bug that v5 shipped.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ef6b00c7-a9bd-49bb-96ad-f3014243d82f"],

Cell["2.3.1  A normalisation cautionary tale (the v5 Coriolis bug)", \
"Subsubsection",ExpressionUUID->"a1c0ffee-1000-4a10-9001-c0de0de00001"],

Cell["\<\
The solver (pyshtools) uses REAL, 4\[Pi]-normalised spherical harmonics. In \
that convention the l=1, m=0 harmonic is \!\(\*SubsuperscriptBox[\(Y\), \
\(1\), \(0\)]\) = \!\(\*SqrtBox[\(3\)]\) cos\[Theta] = \!\(\*SqrtBox[\(3\)]\) \
sin\[Phi]; its peak value at the pole is \!\(\*SqrtBox[\(3\)]\), NOT the \!\(\
\*SqrtBox[\(3/4\[Pi]\)]\) of the more familiar orthonormal (unit-normalised) \
convention. To represent f = 2\[CapitalOmega] sin\[Phi] you need the \
coefficient c with c\[ThinSpace]\!\(\*SqrtBox[\(3\)]\) sin\[Phi] = 2\
\[CapitalOmega] sin\[Phi], i.e. c = 2\[CapitalOmega]/\!\(\*SqrtBox[\(3\)]\).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a1c0ffee-1000-4a10-9001-c0de0de00002"],

Cell["\<\
v5 instead used c = 2\[CapitalOmega]\!\(\*SqrtBox[\(4\[Pi]/3\)]\) \[Dash] the \
coefficient that is correct only for UNIT-normalised harmonics \[Dash] while \
feeding it to 4\[Pi]-normalised ones. Because the 4\[Pi]-normalised harmonics \
are larger by a factor \!\(\*SqrtBox[\(4\[Pi]\)]\) \[TildeTilde] 3.545, the \
planetary vorticity came out too large by exactly that factor. The intended \
\[CapitalOmega] = 40 behaved like an effective \[CapitalOmega] \[TildeTilde] \
142, and f at the pole was \[TildeTilde] 283 instead of 80. v6 uses c = 2\
\[CapitalOmega]/\!\(\*SqrtBox[\(3\)]\), giving f(pole) = 2\[CapitalOmega] = \
80 exactly. The lesson: a spectral coefficient is meaningless until you state \
the normalisation of the basis it multiplies.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a1c0ffee-1000-4a10-9001-c0de0de00003"],

Cell["\<\
With[{\[CapitalOmega] = 40},
 Association[
  \"Y10 peak (4\[Pi]-norm, at pole)\" -> Sqrt[3] // N,
  \"v6 coefficient  2\[CapitalOmega]/Sqrt[3]\" -> 2 \[CapitalOmega]/Sqrt[3] \
// N,
  \"=> f(pole) = coeff*peak\" -> (2 \[CapitalOmega]/Sqrt[3]) Sqrt[3] // N,
  \"v5 coefficient  2\[CapitalOmega]Sqrt[4\[Pi]/3]\" -> 2 \[CapitalOmega] \
Sqrt[4 Pi/3] // N,
  \"=> v5 effective f(pole)\" -> 2 \[CapitalOmega] Sqrt[4 Pi/3] Sqrt[3] // N,
  \"overstatement factor  Sqrt[4\[Pi]]\" -> Sqrt[4 Pi] // N]]
(* f(pole) should be 80; v5 delivered ~283, i.e. \
Sqrt[4\[Pi]]\[TildeTilde]3.545x too large. *)\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"a1c0ffee-1000-4a10-9001-c0de0de00004"],

Cell["\<\
Visualise f on the sphere. It is antisymmetric about the equator: positive \
(red) in the northern hemisphere, negative (blue) in the south.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"56a9cabf-898b-4b9a-90d9-572a2d83d502"],

Cell["\<\
SphericalPlot3D[1, {\[Theta], 0, Pi}, {\[Phi], 0, 2 Pi},
 ColorFunction -> Function[{x, y, z, \[Theta], \[Phi], r},
   (* f \[Proportional] sin(latitude) = cos(\[Theta]) *)
   ColorData[\"TemperatureMap\"][(Cos[\[Theta]] + 1)/2]],
 ColorFunctionScaling -> False, Mesh -> None, PlotPoints -> 60,
 Boxed -> False, Axes -> False, ImageSize -> 380,
 PlotLabel -> Style[\"Coriolis parameter  f = 2\[CapitalOmega] sin\[Phi]\", \
13, Bold]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"54edd68a-2606-4207-a649-85ee73fd9e3c"],

Cell["2.4  Spherical harmonics as basis functions", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"4eebc5a8-303d-477b-881c-9d3a2928adc0"],

Cell["\<\
Spherical harmonics \!\(\*SubsuperscriptBox[\(Y\), \(l\), \(m\)]\)(\[Theta], \
\[Phi]) are the natural Fourier basis on the sphere. Every square-integrable \
field on the sphere expands as\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"64888cc3-dbaa-4c01-a271-3a899271c5e7"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"\[Omega]", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"\[Theta]", ",", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}], "=", 
   UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
    RowBox[{"l", "=", "0"}], "\[Infinity]"], 
   UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
    RowBox[{"m", "=", 
     RowBox[{"-", "l"}]}], "l"], 
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "l", "m"], " ", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["Y", "l", "m"], 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"\[Theta]", ",", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"1e039c00-1490-4941-9c14-922a81b43be9"],

Cell["\<\
with \[Theta] the colatitude and \[Phi] the longitude. Each harmonic \
factorises into an associated Legendre function in latitude and a complex \
exponential in longitude:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f2d28d62-5cc7-434d-94d5-f424853cc646"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["Y", "l", "m"], 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"\[Theta]", ",", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}], "=", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["N", "l", "m"], " ", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["P", "l", "m"], 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"cos", " ", "\[Theta]"}], ")"}], " ", 
   SuperscriptBox["\[ExponentialE]", 
    RowBox[{"\[ImaginaryI]", " ", "m", " ", "\[Phi]"}]]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"a41b9557-a5a7-4e61-a8ed-3a658223377b"],

Cell["The two integer indices have direct physical meaning:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"08c4b751-b388-4772-a894-f4b91630bdae"],

Cell["\<\
The degree l sets the total horizontal wavenumber \[Dash] the number of nodal \
circles on the sphere. Large l = small spatial scale. The characteristic \
angular wavelength is 2\[Pi]/\!\(\*SqrtBox[\(l \((l + 1)\)\)]\).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"ac7b8785-e0ae-4ff5-91f4-73d87fdac909"],

Cell["\<\
The order m sets how much of that structure is in longitude: m nodal \
meridians. Sectoral harmonics (m = l) are the striped, banana-like patterns \
aligned with the rotation axis; zonal harmonics (m = 0) are pure latitude \
bands.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"a46e0987-0d7d-4049-bf61-98ffff349cbe"],

Cell["\<\
The gallery below shows how (l, m) sets a spatial scale and shape. Large m \
produces elongated, axis-aligned stripes. These resemble the \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]banana cells\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] of rotating \
convection, but the resemblance is superficial \[Dash] it is a property of \
the harmonic itself, not evidence that the 2-D model organises the flow this \
way.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"14b7695c-08da-4649-a59f-cdba69ca9184"],

Cell["\<\
(* each row uses valid orders m = 0, l/2, l for its degree l *)
Grid[Table[
  Table[
   SphericalPlot3D[1, {\[Theta], 0, Pi}, {\[Phi], 0, 2 Pi},
    ColorFunction -> Function[{x, y, z, \[Theta], \[Phi], r},
      ColorData[\"TemperatureMap\"][
       Rescale[Re[SphericalHarmonicY[l, m, \[Theta], \[Phi]]], {-0.45, \
0.45}]]],
    ColorFunctionScaling -> False, Mesh -> None, PlotPoints -> 45,
    Boxed -> False, Axes -> False, ImageSize -> 165,
    PlotLabel -> Row[{\"l=\", l, \", m=\", m}]],
   {m, {0, l/2, l}}],
  {l, {4, 8}}],
 Frame -> All, FrameStyle -> LightGray]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"960afc79-26a4-40c4-9f1f-1883fa415e61"],

Cell["\<\
Zonal harmonics (m = 0, left column) are pure latitude bands. As m grows \
toward l (right column) the pattern breaks into longitudinal stripes; the \
sectoral harmonics m = l are the axis-aligned bands. Rotating 3-D convection \
does tend to favour axis-aligned structures, but that selection is a Taylor\
\[Dash]Proudman effect the 2-D model lacks. Here these are just basis \
functions, shown to build intuition for the (l, m) indexing.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2311063f-04d1-4c35-ad49-704f71d1f3fa"],

Cell["2.5  The Jacobian: nonlinear advection, computed spectrally", \
"Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"8f6032dc-0dd0-4073-aa80-ab5c911ca4bb"],

Cell["\<\
The advection term is the Jacobian operator, which on the unit sphere is\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b36b29e0-613e-4341-af4c-5a6f79ca2dbd"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"J", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"A", ",", "B"}], ")"}], "=", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "A"}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Phi]"}]], 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "B"}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Lambda]"}]], "-", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "A"}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Lambda]"}]], 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "B"}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Phi]"}]]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",\

 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"188b2a04-11fd-474a-ac22-a241d9a92198"],

Cell["\<\
with \[Lambda] longitude and \[Phi] latitude. Geometrically J(A, B) measures \
how much the contours of A and B cross: it is the rate at which the flow \
along contours of A advects the field B. Setting A = \[Psi] and B = \
\[Omega]+f gives the advection of absolute vorticity by the streamfunction \
flow.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"992406e7-0f37-48b4-b1ea-e78daade4abd"],

Cell["\<\
A pseudo-spectral evaluation is the standard trick and exactly what \
simulate_v6.py does. Products are cheap in physical (grid) space; derivatives \
are cheap in spectral space. So each step:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8759192e-5925-4a11-88d8-477f0be2534b"],

Cell["\<\
1. Transform \[Psi] and \[Omega]+f to spectral coefficients; multiply by the \
appropriate wavenumbers to get the horizontal gradients.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"ca7afabc-6b83-445a-93a3-0028aea5d344"],

Cell["2. Transform those gradient fields back to the grid.", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"65d05024-cc85-43ea-ab70-e08108c53c67"],

Cell["\<\
3. Form the products and the difference pointwise on the grid \[Dash] this is \
J on the grid.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"21cb1428-25e8-42d2-b0c4-0e46d12a2a73"],

Cell["\<\
4. Transform the result back to spectral space for the time step.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c28cb5ad-6672-4498-a075-9c2b5599a370"],

Cell["\<\
The forward/inverse spherical-harmonic transforms are the workhorse; \
everything else is elementwise arithmetic. (pyshtools performs the \
transforms; the code multiplies gradient components exactly as in the formula \
above.)\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"32f1a74b-1fbe-4280-96df-46cb4f005c35"],

Cell["3.  Key Dimensionless Numbers", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"f16ef2c7-70a1-4bdf-b990-b88cfa87733f"],

Cell["\<\
Whether convection is rotation-dominated, and what structures it forms, is \
decided by a handful of dimensionless ratios. They compare the competing \
forces \[Dash] buoyancy, rotation, viscosity, thermal diffusion \[Dash] and \
locate the flow in parameter space.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b0ecb8a9-416e-4b47-a4c2-972812718695"],

Cell["3.1  The four governing numbers", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"0950d57c-fbaa-4acf-a2b1-261a614ccbeb"],

Cell["\<\
Let d be the shell thickness, \[CapitalDelta]T the superadiabatic temperature \
contrast, g gravity, \[Alpha] the thermal expansion coefficient, \[Nu] \
kinematic viscosity, \[Kappa] thermal diffusivity, \[CapitalOmega] the \
rotation rate, and U, L a characteristic velocity and length of the flow.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fa75ef41-84ce-443e-9503-2eceb3b70f18"],

Cell["Rayleigh number \[Dash] buoyancy vs diffusion", "Subsubsection",ExpressionUUID->"1947df59-28cb-4a89-8186-b3a141226fe6"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"Ra", "=", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"g", " ", "\[Alpha]", " ", "\[CapitalDelta]T", " ", 
     SuperscriptBox["d", "3"]}], 
    RowBox[{"\[Nu]", " ", "\[Kappa]"}]]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",\

 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"7443b980-5be5-47bd-ab06-c951b8fc6c13"],

Cell["\<\
The ratio of buoyant driving to the damping of viscosity and thermal \
diffusion. Above a critical value convection sets in; the Sun runs at Ra \!\(\
\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[TildeTilde] 10\), \(20\[Dash]24\)]\), stupendously \
supercritical \[Dash] fully turbulent.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"12b0810a-6e85-4440-be28-46fd05aeaefa"],

Cell["Ekman number \[Dash] viscosity vs rotation", "Subsubsection",ExpressionUUID->"1d831026-8c20-4549-abf0-5e16dae64933"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"Ek", "=", 
   FractionBox["\[Nu]", 
    RowBox[{"2", " ", "\[CapitalOmega]", " ", 
     SuperscriptBox["d", "2"]}]]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"39e636b5-07ef-4c1c-9591-4cbe4d2a4b99"],

Cell["\<\
The ratio of viscous to Coriolis forces. The solar value is minuscule, Ek \
\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[TildeTilde] 10\), \(-15\)]\) or smaller: rotation \
utterly dominates viscosity. Small Ek is the hallmark of a rapidly rotating \
system.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"01875651-3fec-4b1a-a9ea-441cb27b2248"],

Cell["Prandtl number \[Dash] momentum vs heat diffusion", "Subsubsection",ExpressionUUID->"b496885a-808a-490c-a256-c5febc3eb986"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"Pr", "=", 
   FractionBox["\[Nu]", "\[Kappa]"]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"69f161c0-1375-4224-85ac-4425fda61fe9"],

Cell["\<\
A property of the fluid itself. In stellar plasma Pr \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\
\[TildeTilde] 10\), \(-6\)]\) (heat diffuses far faster than momentum), \
though most simulations, ours included, use an effective turbulent Pr of \
order unity.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1ba651f6-0308-4dee-a985-f9752fc01cd2"],

Cell["Rossby number \[Dash] inertia vs rotation", "Subsubsection",ExpressionUUID->"c904d009-e01e-4975-b491-45babc822d2f"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"Ro", "=", 
   FractionBox["U", 
    RowBox[{"2", " ", "\[CapitalOmega]", " ", "L"}]]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"98d44892-72e4-4bc5-8a04-fe28604a4856"],

Cell["\<\
The single most diagnostic number for the flow structure. Ro \[LessLess] 1 \
means the Coriolis force dominates fluid inertia and the flow is strongly \
rotationally constrained. The solar convection zone has Ro \[TildeTilde] 0.1\
\[Dash]1 depending on scale: the large scales are rotationally constrained, \
the small granular scales are not. The model is run at high \[CapitalOmega] \
(= 40 here), which does place the resolved flow at low Rossby number (Ro \
\[TildeTilde] 0.06 at the forcing scale). But low Ro alone does not hand a \
2-D model the axis-aligned columns of 3-D rotating convection \[Dash] that \
requires the Taylor\[Dash]Proudman constraint (Section 3.2), which is absent \
here. In practice the run stays close to isotropic, with only ~3.7% of its \
energy in zonal (m = 0) modes (Section 6).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9a86f54c-b8ac-49be-860a-b3f0712a8ae2"],

Cell["3.2  The Taylor\[Dash]Proudman theorem", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"3ba69768-c6e3-4863-9714-1ec8c6f6dc8e"],

Cell["\<\
Why does rapid rotation produce columns? Consider a steady, slow, inviscid \
flow. In the rotating frame the leading-order momentum balance is between the \
Coriolis force and the pressure gradient \[Dash] geostrophic balance:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2fb8db4f-a677-4497-98e5-7add358b54ed"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"2", " ", 
   OverscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "\[RightVector]"], "\[Cross]", 
   OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "=", "-", 
   FractionBox["1", "\[Rho]"], 
   RowBox[{"\[Del]", "p"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"ed50e1aa-d6c1-4678-bafe-9ccff2122e20"],

Cell["\<\
Take the curl of both sides. The right-hand side vanishes (the curl of a \
gradient is zero, for constant \[Rho]), and with \
\[Del]\[CenterDot]\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(\[RightVector]\)]\) = 0 the \
left side collapses to a beautifully simple statement:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c25f492f-ce0b-453e-a502-6537afd0659f"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{
     OverscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", 
     "\[Del]"}], ")"}], 
   OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "=", "0"}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"768b349f-773c-46e4-b8b5-9e618875d137"],

Cell["\<\
The velocity field cannot vary along the direction of the rotation axis. If \
\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(\[CapitalOmega]\), \(\[RightVector]\)]\) points along \
\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(z\), \(^\)]\), then \
\[PartialD]\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(\[RightVector]\)]\)/\[PartialD]z = 0: \
the flow is two-dimensional, identical on every plane perpendicular to the \
axis. This is the Taylor\[Dash]Proudman theorem. A rotating fluid is \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]stiff\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] along the axis \[Dash] \
it moves in rigid columns known as Taylor columns.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"861ca327-a464-48a3-9bcd-4637a16e34bf"],

Cell["\<\
In a sphere, convection constrained to remain columnar wraps these columns \
around the inner core, producing the north\[Dash]south elongated \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]banana cells\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] first described \
by Busse (1970). It is tempting to argue that this justifies a 2-D model: if \
rapid rotation makes the 3-D flow nearly two-dimensional, why not model it in \
2-D directly? The argument fails on a crucial point. Taylor\[Dash]Proudman \
makes the flow invariant ALONG the rotation axis \[Dash] a direction that \
lies in the equatorial PLANE, not on the spherical surface this barotropic \
model uses. The model here evolves vorticity on a sphere; it has no axis to \
be stiff along and cannot represent Taylor columns at all. The derivation \
below is background for why rotating convection is columnar in reality \
\[Dash] not a mechanism present in this model.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c606523c-38df-4891-a94e-46abe4cae085"],

Cell["\<\
The cell below makes the constraint visible: convection columns aligned with \
the rotation axis, wrapping the tangent cylinder that circumscribes the inner \
core. This illustrates the real 3-D geometry \[Dash] which the 2-D surface \
model does not contain.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"cb49e9bb-657e-41c4-9ff0-9ae4cbf915fb"],

Cell["\<\
Module[{axis, tanCyl, columns, sph, nCol = 14, rIn = 0.35},
 sph = {Opacity[0.08], Gray, Sphere[{0, 0, 0}, 1]};
 axis = {Thick, Black, Arrow[Tube[{{0, 0, -1.25}, {0, 0, 1.35}}, 0.006]]};
 (* tangent cylinder: circumscribes the inner core *)
 tanCyl = {Opacity[0.12], Blue,
   Cylinder[{{0, 0, -Sqrt[1 - rIn^2]}, {0, 0, Sqrt[1 - rIn^2]}}, rIn]};
 (* banana columns just outside the tangent cylinder *)
 columns = Table[
   With[{s = 0.62, a = 2 Pi k/nCol},
    {ColorData[\"TemperatureMap\"][Mod[k, 2]], Opacity[0.85],
     Cylinder[{{s Cos[a], s Sin[a], -Sqrt[1 - s^2]},
       {s Cos[a], s Sin[a], Sqrt[1 - s^2]}}, 0.05]}],
   {k, 0, nCol - 1}];
 Graphics3D[{sph, tanCyl, columns, axis,
   Text[Style[\"\[CapitalOmega]\", 16, Bold], {0, 0, 1.45}]},
  Boxed -> False, ImageSize -> 400, ViewPoint -> {2.4, -1.8, 1.3},
  PlotLabel -> Style[\"Taylor columns aligned with the rotation axis\", 13, \
Bold]]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"c0c16183-28c5-4bf8-9864-b1a43edacd89"],

Cell["\<\
3.3  Why rotation forces columns \[Dash] a one-line scaling argument\
\>", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"b5717bc9-d359-4608-91ac-973c6914512a"],

Cell["\<\
The Taylor\[Dash]Proudman result can be read as a scaling statement. Vertical \
variations of the flow are suppressed by a factor of the Rossby number: a \
structure of horizontal scale L develops vertical variation only over a \
height \[TildeTilde] L / Ro. When Ro \[LessLess] 1 that height exceeds the \
domain, so the structure spans it as a column. Rapidly rotating convection is \
therefore generically columnar in three dimensions. This explains why 3-D \
convection looks the way it does \[Dash] but it is a statement about vertical \
(axis-parallel) structure, which the 2-D barotropic model does not represent. \
The simulation does NOT reproduce banana cells.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9133c0fe-0a16-4f16-bf8a-7c2819fbd905"],

Cell["4.  The Numerical Method", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"a716fa7a-5637-462b-ae54-bee622c56961"],

Cell["\<\
The solver is spectral: it represents \[Omega] by its spherical-harmonic \
coefficients \!\(\*SubsuperscriptBox[\(\[Omega]\), \(l\), \(m\)]\) and steps \
those coefficients forward in time. Two properties of spherical harmonics \
make this the natural choice on a sphere.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fdd22691-84de-4208-ae99-aadd217da033"],

Cell["4.1  Spherical harmonics diagonalise the Laplacian", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"40a4a7f9-7dd0-4d5c-83c5-a3755444d862"],

Cell["\<\
The single most useful fact for the whole method: spherical harmonics are \
eigenfunctions of the horizontal Laplacian, with eigenvalue -l(l+1) (on the \
unit sphere):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"55397518-2851-4b75-81d7-2e66d6155bfb"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["Y", "l", "m"]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", "l", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}], " ", 
    SubsuperscriptBox["Y", "l", "m"]}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",\

 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"7b3c2be2-27a9-492f-b824-b22ce8f361e4"],

Cell["\<\
Differential operators become multiplication by numbers. Inverting the \
Laplacian to get the streamfunction from the vorticity \[Dash] a global \
Poisson solve \[Dash] is then a single division per mode:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d8e30b9b-35bf-4eb1-a9ce-bcca34488819"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "l", "m"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox[
     RowBox[{"-", "1"}], 
     RowBox[{"l", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}]], " ", 
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "l", "m"]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"8f231137-649f-43b9-a295-eec4b793df46"],

Cell["\<\
This is the array _inv_ev in simulate_v6.py. The l = 0 mode is set to zero (a \
constant streamfunction carries no flow). Let us verify the eigenvalue \
property symbolically \[Dash] apply the angular (Laplace\[Dash]Beltrami) \
operator to \!\(\*SubsuperscriptBox[\(Y\), \(l\), \(m\)]\) and divide it back \
out:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7f7298ba-65c6-4eb8-a381-3fe0469f4971"],

Cell["\<\
angularLaplacian[f_, \[Theta]_, \[Phi]_] :=
  1/Sin[\[Theta]] D[Sin[\[Theta]] D[f, \[Theta]], \[Theta]] + \
1/Sin[\[Theta]]^2 D[f, {\[Phi], 2}];

Table[
  Simplify[
   angularLaplacian[SphericalHarmonicY[l, m, \[Theta], \[Phi]], \[Theta], \
\[Phi]] /
    SphericalHarmonicY[l, m, \[Theta], \[Phi]]],
  {l, 0, 4}, {m, 0, 0}]
(* returns {0, -2, -6, -12, -20} = -l(l+1) *)\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"7a2e2b32-b2e4-48e7-852f-a1c32c26b352"],

Cell["\<\
The output {0, -2, -6, -12, -20} is exactly -l(l+1) for l = 0\[Ellipsis]4. \
The eigenvalue depends only on l, never on m \[Dash] all 2l+1 harmonics of a \
given degree share the same scale.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"04bcf4f2-b1df-41c1-beb0-02e34627f166"],

Cell["\<\
4.2  Hyperviscosity: \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[Del]\), \(8\)]\) instead of \
\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[Del]\), \(2\)]\)\
\>", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"085ffbff-e409-430f-b393-4acb62831b1a"],

Cell["\<\
A real fluid dissipates through ordinary viscosity, \
\[Nu]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[Del]\), \(2\)]\)\[Omega], whose spectral \
damping rate scales as l(l+1). But at the Sun's Ekman number a faithful \[Nu] \
would be so tiny that the smallest resolved scales, unable to dissipate, \
would pile up enstrophy and blow up the run. The fix is hyperviscosity: \
replace \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[Del]\), \(2\)]\) with a higher power. This \
solver uses \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[Del]\), \(8\)]\), whose damping rate \
scales as [l(l+1)\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(]\), \(4\)]\):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c98587da-70c8-4de9-b8f0-8be009b36375"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"damping", " ", "rate"}], 
    RowBox[{"(", "l", ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"\[Mu]", "+", "\[Nu]", " ", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"l", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}], ")"}], "4"]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"ef58e6a8-6f5b-4944-9820-5bd08b80908f"],

Cell["\<\
The key difference is selectivity. Because the exponent is so high, \
hyperviscosity is essentially inert across the whole inertial range and then \
switches on abruptly near the truncation wavenumber, cleanly absorbing the \
enstrophy that cascades to the grid scale while leaving the physically \
meaningful large and intermediate scales almost untouched. The plot compares \
the two, both normalised to bite at the same rate at l = 127:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9743493a-2346-4378-b16b-34ac23d9dcee"],

Cell["\<\
With[{lmax = 127, mu = 0.03, nu = 6.*^-17, dt = 0.0015},
 Module[{lam, hyper, ord, nuOrd},
  lam[l_] := l (l + 1);
  (* match ordinary viscosity to hyperviscosity at the truncation *)
  nuOrd = nu lam[lmax]^4/lam[lmax];
  hyper[l_] := nu lam[l]^4;
  ord[l_] := nuOrd lam[l];
  LogPlot[{ord[l], hyper[l]}, {l, 1, lmax},
   PlotRange -> All, PlotPoints -> 200,
   PlotStyle -> {{Gray, Dashed}, {RGBColor[0.8, 0.1, 0.1], Thick}},
   PlotLegends -> Placed[{\"ordinary \[Nu]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[Del]\), \
\(2\)]\)  (rate \[Proportional] l(l+1))\",
      \"hyperviscosity \[Nu]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[Del]\), \(8\)]\)  (rate \
\[Proportional] [l(l+1)\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(]\), \(4\)]\))\"}, Below],
   Frame -> True, GridLines -> {{60, 80}, None},
   FrameLabel -> {\"spherical-harmonic degree l\", \"dissipation rate\"},
   ImageSize -> 440,
   PlotLabel -> Style[\"Scale-selective dissipation\", 13, Bold]]]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"ebe7a55c-dd5f-4f4e-8a31-c25f88d2f0fb"],

Cell["\<\
The two vertical gridlines mark the forcing band (l = 60\[Dash]80). Ordinary \
viscosity (dashed) already damps those forced scales appreciably; \
hyperviscosity (red) is orders of magnitude weaker there and only rises to \
meet it at the very smallest scales \[Dash] preserving a broad inertial range \
of thin vorticity filaments. (Note the flip side, quantified in the audit \
section: with the forcing this close to the truncation, ~42% of the injected \
energy is removed by hyperviscosity at small scales instead of cascading \
upscale.)\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f9a16040-2a82-472e-862f-f371e59f1bb4"],

Cell["4.3  The implicit dissipation factor and RK2 time stepping", \
"Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"0827b064-e8f6-4110-a96f-ce0a48cc0bae"],

Cell["\<\
Dissipation is handled with an integrating factor, applied as an exact \
multiplicative decay each step \[Dash] unconditionally stable regardless of \
how fast the smallest scales damp:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"167db4a8-22b7-4890-b362-60e5be72dda5"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "l", "m"], "=", 
   RowBox[{"exp", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"-", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"\[Mu]", "+", "\[Nu]", 
        SuperscriptBox[
         RowBox[{"(", 
          RowBox[{"l", 
           RowBox[{"(", 
            RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}], ")"}], "4"]}], ")"}], 
      "\[CapitalDelta]t"}], ")"}], " ", 
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "l", "m"]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"b6bdcfbb-45bc-49fe-b6fd-4f1c7643db0b"],

Cell["\<\
The advective (nonlinear) part is advanced explicitly with a two-stage Runge\
\[Dash]Kutta scheme (Heun's method): a predictor \!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(k\), \
\(1\)]\), a corrector \!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(k\), \(2\)]\) evaluated at the \
predicted state, and the average:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c0c48cfc-5d7b-4054-88f3-36ef4c4ecd50"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["k", "1"], "=", "\[ScriptCapitalN]", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       SuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "n"], ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["k", "2"], "=", "\[ScriptCapitalN]", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{
        SuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "n"], "+", "\[CapitalDelta]t", " ", 
        SubscriptBox["k", "1"]}], ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", 
       RowBox[{"n", "+", "1"}]], "=", "\[ScriptCapitalD]", "\[CenterDot]", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{
        SuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "n"], "+", 
        FractionBox["\[CapitalDelta]t", "2"], 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{
          SubscriptBox["k", "1"], "+", 
          SubscriptBox["k", "2"]}], ")"}], "+", "F"}], ")"}]}]}
   }], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"69afdc84-51b3-4fd5-bc86-054095a8ada1"],

Cell["\<\
where \[ScriptCapitalN] = -J(\[Psi], \[Omega]+f) is the advective tendency, F \
is the stochastic forcing added at each step, and \[ScriptCapitalD] is the \
implicit dissipation factor above. This is exactly the sequence in the step() \
method: two tendency evaluations, add forcing, multiply by the viscosity \
factor, and zero out the mean.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c245c43d-d1ea-4134-b523-e82efbf0c08e"],

Cell["\<\
A word on global accuracy, to be honest about it. The advective substep is a \
2nd-order Heun step and the dissipation factor is EXACT, but the two are \
combined by simple operator splitting (Lie\[Dash]Trotter: advance advection, \
then apply the linear factor). Lie\[Dash]Trotter splitting is only \
first-order accurate, so the scheme as a whole is globally \
O(\[CapitalDelta]t), NOT 2nd order. A step-halving test confirms it \[Dash] \
the deterministic error ratio is 2.00, the signature of first-order \
convergence. For statistically steady, strongly dissipative turbulence driven \
by white-in-time forcing this is adequate (the strong order under such \
forcing is \[LessEqual] 1 regardless), but the scheme should not be \
advertised as 2nd-order. A Strang split, \
\[ScriptCapitalD](\[CapitalDelta]t/2)\[VeryThinSpace]\[ScriptCapitalN](\
\[CapitalDelta]t)\[VeryThinSpace]\[ScriptCapitalD](\[CapitalDelta]t/2), would \
recover 2nd order in the deterministic limit.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c245c43d-d1ea-4134-b523-e82efbf0c08f"],

Cell["4.4  Stochastic forcing as a proxy for buoyancy", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"dd12c2b1-d6bb-4c52-a3fe-6985c973f72e"],

Cell["\<\
The barotropic model has no temperature field, so there is nothing to \
generate buoyancy. Instead the stirring is imposed directly, by injecting \
random vorticity each step in a band of small scales (degrees l = 60\[Dash]80 \
in v6), chosen to sit ABOVE the Rhines degree (measured l_R \[TildeTilde] 23) \
so that a forward enstrophy cascade runs to smaller scales (filaments, \
absorbed by hyperviscosity) and SOME inverse energy transfer runs to larger \
scales (partly removed by the weak linear drag). The amplitude in each mode \
is scaled by 1/\!\(\*SqrtBox[\(l \((l + 1)\)\)]\) and by \!\(\*SqrtBox[\(\
\[CapitalDelta]t\)]\) so the injection behaves as a proper white-in-time \
forcing. After a spin-up of ~5 drag times the run reaches a statistically \
steady state. Note the scale separation is only marginal (l_R \[TildeTilde] \
23 vs forcing 60\[Dash]80, ratio ~2.6), so the inverse cascade is weak and \
does NOT organise into jets \[Dash] see Section 6 and the audit.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5a6035ee-767b-4023-bfb1-4e1dd812359c"],

Cell["\<\
(* the forcing spectrum: amplitude injected per mode vs degree l *)
Module[{lmin = 60, lmax = 80, amp = 2.2},
 BarChart[
  Table[If[lmin <= l <= lmax, amp/Sqrt[l (l + 1)], 0], {l, 1, 127}],
  ChartLabels -> None, ChartStyle -> RGBColor[0.85, 0.3, 0.2],
  Frame -> True, FrameLabel -> {\"degree l\", \"forcing amplitude\"},
  PlotLabel -> Style[\"Stochastic forcing band (l = 60\[Dash]80)\", 13, \
Bold],
  ImageSize -> 420]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"2724655c-8065-4735-a880-9c2994c6857a"],

Cell["5.  Visualisation \[Dash] Geometry of the Cutaway", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"44ed1a3a-f7c6-4a1d-9b98-1fdf8d026e7b"],

Cell["\<\
The renderer draws a spherical shell with an octant removed so the interior \
is exposed. This section reconstructs the geometry in Wolfram Language so the \
visual choices are transparent.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b344dc2a-5c90-4529-a258-d0d5db910077"],

Cell["5.1  The shell with an octant cutaway", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"6403f096-9419-4c07-88a2-eb4943575e5c"],

Cell["\<\
The visualiser removes the wedge {0\[Degree] \[LessEqual] longitude < 90\
\[Degree] and latitude > 0} from the outer sphere, exposing an equatorial \
quarter-annulus and two meridional faces, and revealing the inner core. Here \
is the same geometry, with the surface coloured by a sample \
spherical-harmonic field to mimic the vorticity pattern.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"116d1fbd-c416-4ab6-965c-e18da0c5ccc0"],

Cell["\<\
Module[{outer, core, field},
 field[\[Theta]_, \[Phi]_] := Re[SphericalHarmonicY[8, 6, \[Theta], \[Phi]]];
 outer = ParametricPlot3D[
   {Cos[\[Phi]] Cos[\[Lambda]], Cos[\[Phi]] Sin[\[Lambda]], Sin[\[Phi]]},
   {\[Lambda], 0, 2 Pi}, {\[Phi], -Pi/2, Pi/2},
   RegionFunction -> Function[{x, y, z, \[Lambda], \[Phi]},
     Not[0 < \[Lambda] < Pi/2 && z > 0]],
   ColorFunction -> Function[{x, y, z, \[Lambda], \[Phi]},
     ColorData[\"TemperatureMap\"][Rescale[field[Pi/2 - \[Phi], \[Lambda]], \
{-0.4, 0.4}]]],
   ColorFunctionScaling -> False, Mesh -> None, PlotPoints -> 60,
   Boxed -> False, Axes -> False];
 core = Graphics3D[{GrayLevel[0.55], Sphere[{0, 0, 0}, 0.35]}];
 Show[outer, core, ImageSize -> 420,
  ViewPoint -> {2.2, -1.9, 1.2},
  PlotLabel -> Style[\"Spherical shell with octant cutaway\", 13, Bold]]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"c16e69ea-7935-4968-9746-52a5067961fb"],

Cell["5.2  The radial reconstruction on the cut faces", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"a2138e7a-b5ad-40d4-a77a-b917f2bb333e"],

Cell["\<\
The barotropic model lives on a single spherical surface \[Dash] it has no \
genuine radial structure. To draw a cutaway we must nonetheless say something \
about \[Omega] INSIDE the shell. v6 replaces v5's decorative decay with the \
correct RADIAL EIGENFUNCTION: each spherical-harmonic mode is continued \
inward by the regular solid harmonic \
\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\((r/\*SubscriptBox[\(R\), \(out\)])\), \(l\)]\) \[Dash] \
the solution of Laplace's equation \[Del]^2(\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(r\), \
\(l\)]\)\!\(\*SubsuperscriptBox[\(Y\), \(l\), \(m\)]\)) = 0 that stays finite \
toward the origin, hence the natural radial structure of a harmonic scalar \
field. Written per mode:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0951d413-5635-4f9e-a72e-cb9590ff477e"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[Omega]", "(", 
    RowBox[{"r", ",", "\[Theta]", ",", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    UnderscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     RowBox[{"l", ",", "m"}]], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "l", "m"], " ", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"r", "/", 
       SubscriptBox["R", "out"]}], ")"}], "l"], " ", 
    RowBox[{
     SubsuperscriptBox["Y", "l", "m"], "(", 
     RowBox[{"\[Theta]", ",", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"033e3327-c331-48fd-b0a1-67a8ed41b397"],

Cell["\<\
The factor \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\((r/\*SubscriptBox[\(R\), \(out\)])\), \
\(l\)]\) does two honest things at once. At r = \!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(R\), \
\(out\)]\) it equals 1, so the cut faces join the coloured surface seamlessly \
\[Dash] no longitude shear needed. And because it decays faster the larger l \
is, low-l (large-scale) structures reach deep into the shell while high-l \
filaments stay surface-confined \[Dash] the depth ordering is DERIVED from \
the harmonic degree, not painted on. The plot shows the weight for a few \
degrees; note how completely the forcing scale (l \[TildeTilde] 70) dies \
before reaching the base at r/R = 0.71.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c162bd4d-c13e-44d7-9e32-45ee77e795a9"],

Cell["\<\
Module[{rIn = 0.71, rOut = 1.0, ls = {2, 6, 20, 70}},
 Plot[Evaluate[Table[(r/rOut)^l, {l, ls}]], {r, rIn, rOut},
  PlotRange -> {0, 1}, PlotStyle -> {Red, Purple, Darker[Green], Blue},
  Frame -> True, FrameLabel -> {\"radius r / R\", \"radial weight (r/R)^l\"},
  PlotLegends -> ((\"l = \" <> ToString[#]) & /@ ls),
  GridLines -> {{rIn, rOut}, {0, 1}}, ImageSize -> 440,
  PlotLabel -> Style[\"Regular solid-harmonic radial weight (r/R)^l\", 13, \
Bold]]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"bd17a0de-b326-462c-a3ab-2fcb49e5e0d8"],

Cell["\<\
HONESTY, as flagged in the v6 audit (\[Section]4.4): the exact \
\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\((r/R)\), \(l\)]\) above puts a forcing-scale mode (l \
\[TildeTilde] 70) at \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(0.71\), \(70\)]\) \[TildeTilde] 4\
\[Times]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(10\), \(-11\)]\) of its surface amplitude at \
the base \[Dash] i.e. the deep interior is essentially empty of small-scale \
structure. To fill the cutaway for display, the actual renderer \
(visualize_v6.py) softens the decay to \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\((r/R)\), \
\(l/\*SubscriptBox[\(L\), \(ref\)])\)]\) with \!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(L\), \(ref\
\)]\) \[TildeTilde] 10, which OVERSTATES the penetration of forcing-scale \
modes by ~10\[Times] (painting l \[TildeTilde] 70 at ~9% at the base). That \
is an illustrative choice to avoid an almost-blank interior, honestly \
labelled as such \[Dash] a 2-D barotropic model carries no radial structure \
at all.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c162bd4d-cc00-49bc-9c00-000000000001"],

Cell["\<\
An equatorial cross-section makes the effect concrete. Taking a single \
longitudinal wave cos(6\[Lambda]) (a stand-in for one l = 6 surface mode) and \
multiplying by its regular-solid-harmonic weight \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\((r/R)\
\), \(6\)]\) gives structure that is strong near the rim and decays smoothly \
inward \[Dash] shell-following, not vertical columns. A 2-D surface field \
simply has no mechanism to make Taylor columns:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1071812a-01ec-4478-8d54-078dccf42efe"],

Cell["\<\
Module[{rIn = 0.71, rOut = 1.0, w, field},
 w[r_] := (r/rOut)^6;
 field[r_, \[Lambda]_] := w[r] Cos[6 \[Lambda]];
 DensityPlot[field[Sqrt[x^2 + y^2], ArcTan[x, y]],
  {x, 0, rOut}, {y, 0, rOut},
  RegionFunction -> Function[{x, y}, rIn <= Sqrt[x^2 + y^2] <= rOut],
  ColorFunction -> (ColorData[\"TemperatureMap\"][Rescale[#, {-1, 1}]] &),
  ColorFunctionScaling -> False, PlotPoints -> 90, Mesh -> None,
  Frame -> True, AspectRatio -> 1, ImageSize -> 360,
  PlotLabel -> Style[\"Equatorial cut: (r/R)^l reconstruction\", 13, Bold]]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"7dbae047-2016-448f-8bef-bb083d0ab649"],

Cell["5.3  A banana-cell pattern on the sphere", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"59a4139b-c4f9-4216-8325-cbe745d5353d"],

Cell["\<\
Finally, a high-order sectoral harmonic (l = m) gives an axis-aligned, north\
\[Dash]south-elongated pattern. Such patterns are the usual illustration of \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]banana cells\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] \[Dash] but, as \
stressed throughout, the 2-D barotropic simulation does not select or \
reproduce them. This cell simply displays one sectoral harmonic in isolation, \
as a picture of what the phrase refers to.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"43826b47-226f-439d-ac52-e69796892ffe"],

Cell["\<\
SphericalPlot3D[1 + 0.06 Re[SphericalHarmonicY[12, 12, \[Theta], \[Phi]]],
 {\[Theta], 0, Pi}, {\[Phi], 0, 2 Pi},
 ColorFunction -> Function[{x, y, z, \[Theta], \[Phi], r},
   ColorData[\"TemperatureMap\"][Rescale[Re[SphericalHarmonicY[12, 12, \
\[Theta], \[Phi]]], {-0.3, 0.3}]]],
 ColorFunctionScaling -> False, Mesh -> None, PlotPoints -> 70,
 Boxed -> False, Axes -> False, ImageSize -> 380,
 PlotLabel -> Style[\"Sectoral harmonic (l = m = 12): an axis-aligned pattern\
\", 13, Bold]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"9e2582ca-708a-4354-90ea-94e400decdd0"],

Cell["6.  Results and Discussion", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"98bdd22b-bdf6-44ba-9aa9-af3ff56b8379"],

Cell["6.1  What the simulation shows", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"8beeb598-a1a9-4e82-806f-e4ff0576fa3c"],

Cell["\<\
Run at high rotation (\[CapitalOmega] = 40, spectral truncation T127) and \
spun up for ~5 drag times, the model settles into a statistically steady, \
rotation-dominated turbulent state. The characteristic features \[Dash] and, \
honestly, the features it was hoped for but does NOT show:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"88296a7a-83bf-4939-ab8a-e44cdd0ee999"],

Cell["\<\
A broad, filamentary vorticity field. The spectrum genuinely broadened \
relative to v5 \[Dash] roughly 53% of the enstrophy below / 31% in / 16% \
above the forcing band, versus v5's 97% trapped in-band \[Dash] so a forward \
enstrophy cascade and some inverse transfer both exist. This is the real, \
measurable v6 improvement.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"48f5e47d-b7a1-4951-b713-2eb4c8b5e87b"],

Cell["\<\
A broad inertial range of thin vorticity filaments, sustained by the weak, \
scale-selective hyperviscosity that only bites near the truncation.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"de0f1207-f1cc-4038-aaa3-6c15f447c339"],

Cell["\<\
A statistically steady balance: stochastic forcing injects at l = \
60\[Dash]80, the forward enstrophy cascade drains to small scales, and linear \
drag removes large-scale energy. (A caveat quantified in the audit: ~42% of \
the injected energy is lost to hyperviscosity at small scales rather than \
cascading upscale, because the forcing sits close to the dissipation range.)\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"133c49cf-5449-41fc-abe2-919832b9262b"],

Cell["\<\
NO zonal jets. The \[Beta]-effect imposes some equator\[Dash]pole anisotropy \
and Rossby-wave activity, but zonal (m = 0) energy is only ~3.7% \[Dash] \
essentially isotropic turbulence with a whisper of anisotropy, NOT a jet \
regime (which would be 50\[Dash]90% zonal). The scale separation that would \
drive jets is marginal (Rhines degree l_R \[TildeTilde] 23 vs forcing 60\
\[Dash]80), so the advertised \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]jets from an arrested \
inverse cascade\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] are NOT achieved at these parameters. \
The legitimate niche of this class of model is Jupiter-like 2-D geostrophic \
turbulence, which this particular run does not reach.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"ccb0dced-f059-4b6f-9e62-3793a3d94b35"],

Cell["6.2  How it compares to full 3-D convection codes", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"c1e9cffd-752a-475d-903d-3e5dd1e044d1"],

Cell["\<\
Global solar-convection models such as ASH (Anelastic Spherical Harmonic; \
Brun & Toomre 2002) and Rayleigh (Featherstone & Hindman 2016) solve the full \
three-dimensional anelastic equations \[Dash] momentum, energy, and often \
induction \[Dash] on a radially resolved spherical shell. Relative to those, \
the barotropic model is a deliberate, extreme simplification.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"38af6edc-7d37-49be-b407-df9ffb4a51c5"],

Cell["\<\
The table summarises what the barotropic model keeps and what it discards.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"dbd6dbfa-5ebe-4a47-b1a7-8eb5ca561ffe"],

Cell["\<\
Grid[{
  {Style[\"Feature\", Bold], Style[\"Barotropic (this model)\", Bold], Style[\
\"3-D anelastic (ASH / Rayleigh)\", Bold]},
  {\"Spatial dimensions\", \"2-D (one spherical surface)\", \"3-D (radially \
resolved shell)\"},
  {\"Prognostic fields\", \"vorticity \[Omega] only\", \"velocity, entropy, \
(magnetic field)\"},
  {\"Rotation / Coriolis\", \"yes (f = 2\[CapitalOmega] sin\[Phi])\", \"yes \
(full Coriolis)\"},
  {\"Buoyancy driving\", \"none (imposed stochastic stirring)\", \"genuine \
thermal buoyancy\"},
  {\"Radial structure\", \"none (reconstructed for display)\", \"resolved\"},
  {\"Differential rotation\", \"not captured\", \"emergent\"},
  {\"Magnetism / dynamo\", \"none\", \"optional (MHD)\"},
  {\"Cost\", \"seconds on a laptop\", \"CPU/GPU-hours on a cluster\"}
  },
 Frame -> All, Background -> {None, {LightYellow, None}},
 Alignment -> Left, Spacings -> {1.2, 1}, ItemSize -> {{12, 16, 18}, \
Automatic}]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"29717eb2-414b-47b5-a4eb-284efad58d29"],

Cell["6.3  What the model gets right \[Dash] and what it misses", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"30aeb8f3-08d3-4603-bec7-cec92e09ea9c"],

Cell["Gets right:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a402a0ba-56cf-4493-bcc4-aa84b6a23dc8"],

Cell["\<\
Rotation-dominated 2-D dynamics. The Coriolis \[Beta]-effect is represented \
exactly, and the resolved flow sits at low Rossby number.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"b1e2da47-ebf0-438f-9983-bd83116c4c17"],

Cell["\<\
The kinematics of non-divergent flow on a rotating sphere: exact vorticity\
\[Dash]streamfunction inversion, planetary-vorticity advection, and \
Rossby-wave propagation.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"8816f450-036a-4ebc-bf4b-25898b4023e2"],

Cell["\<\
The character of forced\[Dash]dissipative 2-D turbulence: a dual cascade \
(forward enstrophy to filaments, some inverse energy transfer), \
filamentation, and a statistically steady state.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"86324233-49f1-4d09-9b6e-87daa109c51a"],

Cell["Misses:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"245a65a5-5deb-4c06-9d17-1e02506fa7f5"],

Cell["\<\
Radial structure. There is no genuine depth dependence; the interior in the \
visualisation is a mapping, not a solution. Real convection has plumes \
spanning the depth of the zone.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"9e0850c7-5471-49d9-9424-a3300504351b"],

Cell["\<\
Differential rotation. The solar equator-fast profile emerges from the \
interaction of convection, rotation, and the meridional circulation \[Dash] \
mean flows the barotropic model cannot self-consistently generate.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"d89fa9be-c915-48fd-b65e-74d2104c7f1b"],

Cell["\<\
Thermal physics and stratification. No temperature equation, no density \
stratification (which makes upflows broad and downflows narrow in the real \
Sun), no superadiabaticity.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"dc83ef9d-cab7-4dde-b7e1-a034f81e9894"],

Cell["\<\
Magnetism. No dynamo, hence no sunspot cycle \[Dash] the phenomenon that \
motivates much of solar-convection research.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"275340bf-1e88-49d7-93f0-ff0037f9daef"],

Cell["\<\
The barotropic model is best understood as a fast, transparent laboratory for \
the geometry and statistics of forced 2-D turbulence on a rotating sphere \
\[Dash] not a model of solar convection, and (at these parameters) not even a \
jet-forming geostrophic-turbulence run. It is a stepping stone to, not a \
replacement for, the full 3-D simulations described next.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9c59226c-4a2c-448d-89c7-bc0102af2f65"],

Cell["7.  What This Model Cannot Capture", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0007-4000-8000-000000000001"],

Cell["\<\
The limitations below are STRUCTURAL \[Dash] they follow from the model being \
a single scalar equation on a 2-D surface, and no amount of parameter tuning \
can remove them. This is the honest boundary of what a barotropic vorticity \
model can say about solar convection.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0007-4000-8000-000000000002"],

Cell["\<\
No radial dimension. The model lives on one spherical surface, so it has no \
depth structure, no penetration or overshoot, no tachocline, and no vertical \
velocity \[Dash] which is precisely the up/down-flow signal that convection \
imagery shows. The interior in the cutaway is a kinematic reconstruction \
(Section 5), not a solved flow.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0007-4000-8000-000000000003"],

Cell["\<\
No buoyancy or energy equation. There is no temperature, no Rayleigh number, \
no convective instability, and no heat transport. The flow is stirred by \
imposed forcing, not driven by buoyancy; the convective scale is prescribed, \
not selected.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0007-4000-8000-000000000004"],

Cell["\<\
No stratification or compressibility. The real Sun spans ~4\[Dash]5 density \
scale heights, which makes upflows broad and downflows narrow; the barotropic \
model is incompressible and uniform.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0007-4000-8000-000000000005"],

Cell["\<\
No Taylor\[Dash]Proudman constraint. This is a genuinely 3-D balance \
(invariance along the rotation axis), so real axis-aligned banana cells \
cannot arise from the correct mechanism in a 2-D surface model (Sections 1.2, \
3.2).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0007-4000-8000-000000000006"],

Cell["\<\
No self-consistent differential rotation. The solar equator-fast profile \
emerges from correlated 3-D velocity components (Reynolds stresses, \
meridional circulation) that a single scalar \[Omega] cannot carry. The \
longitude twist on the cutaway faces is a viewing choice, not solar rotation.\
\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0007-4000-8000-000000000007"],

Cell["\<\
No magnetism. No induction, hence no dynamo, no 11-year cycle, and no \
sunspots \[Dash] the very phenomena that motivate much of solar-convection \
research. To model any of this you need a 3-D anelastic (MHD) code (see the \
References and README_v6.md).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0007-4000-8000-000000000008"],

Cell["8.  The v6 Audit \[Dash] What Is Verified and What Is Not", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0008-4000-8000-000000000001"],

Cell["\<\
v6 is a scientifically honest rebuild of an earlier v5 run whose physics \
claims did not survive scrutiny. Every checkable claim was re-derived and \
tested numerically against the saturated field (v6_critical_audit.md). The \
result is a clear split between a trustworthy SOLVER and a set of claims the \
field does NOT support.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0008-4000-8000-000000000002"],

Cell["Verified correct (the numerics are sound):", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0008-4000-8000-000000000003"],

Cell["\<\
The advection conserves energy and enstrophy to \
~1\[Times]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(10\), \(-6\)]\) per step in an inviscid test \
\[Dash] the strongest single piece of evidence that the barotropic Jacobian \
and time step are correct.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0008-4000-8000-000000000004"],

Cell["\<\
The spherical Jacobian is metric-consistent (built from physical gradient \
components, avoiding the 1/cos\[Phi] singularity) and is effectively \
alias-free (0.07% vs a 2\[Times]-padded reference).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0008-4000-8000-000000000005"],

Cell["\<\
The Coriolis coefficient is fixed to 2\[CapitalOmega]/\!\(\*SqrtBox[\(3\)]\), \
giving f(pole) = 2\[CapitalOmega] = 80 exactly (Section 2.3.1); the \[Del]^8 \
hyperviscosity, the exact integrating-factor dissipation, and the \
\!\(\*SqrtBox[\(\[CapitalDelta]t\)]\) white-noise forcing scaling all check \
out.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0008-4000-8000-000000000006"],

Cell["\<\
Not achieved / honest caveats (properties of the run, not bugs in the solver):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0008-4000-8000-000000000007"],

Cell["\<\
Jets are NOT achieved. Zonal energy is ~3.7% \[Dash] essentially isotropic \
turbulence. The cascade broadened (a real improvement over v5), but the \
marginal Rhines/forcing separation (l_R \[TildeTilde] 23 vs forcing \
60\[Dash]80) and the ~42% energy loss to hyperviscosity keep the inverse \
cascade too weak to organise jets.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0008-4000-8000-000000000008"],

Cell["\<\
The time integration is globally O(\[CapitalDelta]t) (first-order Lie split \
of a Heun advection step with an exact linear factor), not 2nd-order \[Dash] \
verified by a step-halving ratio of 2.00 (Section 4.3).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0008-4000-8000-000000000009"],

Cell["\<\
The interior reconstruction and the cutaway longitude twist are illustrative \
geometry, not solved dynamics; the display softens the true \
\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\((r/R)\), \(l\)]\) decay and so overstates deep \
penetration of forcing-scale modes by ~10\[Times] (Section 5.2). All of this \
is honestly labelled in the code and captions.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0008-4000-8000-00000000000a"],

Cell["\<\
Part II \[LongDash] The Full Physics Programme: All Twenty Improvements\
\>", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee01-0000-4000-8000-000000000001"],

Cell["\<\
Sections 1\[Dash]8 above document the v6 barotropic solver. The project has \
since been extended through twenty scientific improvements \
(scientific_improvements.md), grouped in four tiers: (A) make the barotropic \
model actually demonstrate the physics it claims (items 1\[Dash]8 \[Dash] \
wider scale separation, steady-state averaging, higher-order time stepping, \
controlled forcing, flux diagnostics); (B) extend the physics with new terms \
and new equation sets (items 9\[Dash]14 \[Dash] differential rotation, \
topography, deformation radius, two-layer QG, shallow water, MHD); (C) \
replace the model with real convection (items 15\[Dash]18 \[Dash] Boussinesq \
and anelastic shells, community solvers, Model S stratification); and (D) \
turn output into evidence (items 19\[Dash]20 \[Dash] Lagrangian FTLE, honest \
interior). The sections below give the governing equations, the physical \
meaning of each term, the numerical method, and the key references for every \
improvement. The implementing modules are named in each section.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3446df85-fbc4-474a-9ab8-8167b473f5a2"],

Cell["\<\
Honesty note carried forward from Part I: items 1\[Dash]14 all evolve a 2-D \
scalar field on a surface and are NOT convection \[Dash] they have no \
buoyancy, no energy equation, no vertical velocity. Only items 15\[Dash]18 \
add genuine convection (buoyancy + temperature + a radial dimension). Every \
section states plainly what it does and does not contain.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f465007c-64f6-4ed1-8a78-0a8bc74e1b45"],

Cell["9.  The Complete Governing Equation and Its Spectral Form", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"a987044c-64b8-4d3a-a0fd-1904de6cf8d3"],

Cell["\<\
The equation the v6/v7 barotropic solver integrates, written with every term \
(config_v7.py, simulate_v7.py):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"319f2014-a086-4853-be53-59fa66090289"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Omega]"}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
   RowBox[{"J", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ",", "\[Omega]", "+", "f"}], ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", "\[Nu]", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"-", 
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"]}], ")"}], "4"], "\[Omega]"}], "-", 
   RowBox[{"\[Mu]", " ", "\[Omega]"}], "+", "F"}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"15a40af3-dbc0-4858-9136-914a4f24630c"],

Cell["Reading the terms as physical processes:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"aa82fe2e-7e02-4abb-a226-91f003cb00cb"],

Cell["\<\
\[PartialD]\[Omega]/\[PartialD]t \[Dash] the local rate of change of the \
relative vertical vorticity \[Omega] = \!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(z\), \(^\)]\)\
\[CenterDot](\[Del]\[Cross]\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(\[RightVector]\)]\)), \
the single prognostic scalar of the model.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c0c65098-a18c-4eb1-9e3e-18eb4ac8194e"],

Cell["\<\
J(\[Psi], \[Omega]+f) \[Dash] nonlinear advection of ABSOLUTE vorticity \
\[Omega]+f by the non-divergent flow \!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(\
\[RightVector]\)]\) = \!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(z\), \
\(^\)]\)\[Cross]\[Del]\[Psi]. The advection of the PLANETARY part f by the \
eddies is the \[Beta]-effect; it is the term that makes Rossby waves and, \
ultimately, jets. This nonlinearity is what makes the problem turbulent.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c208e67f-8a16-48de-b3f3-ab7799b96fee"],

Cell["\<\
\[Dash]\[Nu](\[Dash]\[Del]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \
\(2\)]\)\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \(4\)]\)\[Omega] = \
\[Dash]\[Nu]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[Del]\), \(8\)]\)\[Omega] \[Dash] \[Del]\
\[Cedilla] hyperviscosity. In spectral space it multiplies the coefficient by \
\[Dash]\[Nu]\[Lambda]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \(4\)]\) with \[Lambda] = \
l(l+1); the drain time \[Tau] = 1/(\[Nu]\[Lambda]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \
\(4\)]\) is ~0.25 tu at the truncation but ~10\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(0\), \(6\
\)]\) tu at the jet scale, so it removes only the smallest scales (Section 4, \
config_v7 NU_HYPER).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"7ee93209-61d2-48d7-b3e4-32513012289b"],

Cell["\<\
\[Dash]\[Mu]\[Omega] \[Dash] uniform linear (Rayleigh / Ekman) drag, the \
PRIMARY large-scale energy sink. It sets the saturated energy E_sat = \
\[Epsilon]/(2\[Mu]) and arrests the inverse cascade; \[Tau]_drag = 1/\[Mu] is \
the flow's longest memory (100 tu in v7).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"1175e1b9-5f8d-4bad-bacd-b8198fbfa6da"],

Cell["\<\
F \[Dash] stochastic forcing that injects vorticity in a chosen band of \
degrees. It is an imposed stirring, a kinematic stand-in for the convective \
plumes \[Dash] NOT buoyancy, and not selected by any instability (see Section \
11 for its statistics).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"8fb71999-f473-4513-9c55-fdb8fcbcf4f7"],

Cell["9.1  Vorticity\[Dash]streamfunction inversion", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"b4017b19-bdfe-4afd-b34b-a053a841f4dc"],

Cell["\<\
The flow is recovered from the vorticity by inverting the Laplacian. Because \
the spherical harmonics diagonalise \[Del]\.b2 (eigenvalue \[Dash]l(l+1), \
Section 4.1), the inversion is one division per mode:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d17ea0bf-c6cb-4d55-9ddc-776a8f48bffd"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"\[Omega]", "=", 
   SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "\[Psi]", "\[LongRightArrow]", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "lm", ""], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    FractionBox[
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "lm", ""], 
     RowBox[{"l", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}]]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"fb8b5dec-d9ab-4683-af95-04ddad26eb0e"],

Cell["\<\
The equivalent-barotropic generalisation (Section 14.3) replaces the \
denominator l(l+1) by l(l+1)+1/L_d\.b2.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d4d35db8-c371-4267-b282-c8fbd1fb8336"],

Cell["9.2  The Jacobian in physical and spectral space", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"ae1bff96-0035-45d8-82a3-83db67ebe97e"],

Cell["\<\
The advection operator is the Jacobian of two scalars on the sphere,\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f157a1b5-a47b-4a37-a674-7c4a4261155d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"J", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"A", ",", "B"}], ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox["z", "^"], "\[CenterDot]", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"\[Del]", "A", "\[Cross]", "\[Del]", "B"}], ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      OverscriptBox["z", "^"], "\[Cross]", "\[Del]", "A"}], ")"}], "\[CenterDot]",
     "\[Del]", "B"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"3a2d9cfa-bf70-4805-8448-b2ef988c4b61"],

Cell["\<\
i.e. the advection of B by the flow whose streamfunction is A. The solver \
evaluates it PSEUDO-SPECTRALLY and metric-consistently: transform \[Psi] and \
\[Omega]+f to physical gradient components (\[PartialD]\[Theta], (1/sin\
\[Theta])\[PartialD]\[Phi]) with pyshtools, multiply on the grid to form the \
Jacobian, and transform back. Building it from physical gradient components \
(not raw \[PartialD]\[Phi]) avoids the 1/cos\[Phi] pole singularity and is \
alias-free on the oversampled Driscoll\[Dash]Healy grid (Section 8). The \
whole spectral update per mode is\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ec8947c7-e61a-4f7a-bdd8-cf3d13c4e97e"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "lm", ""]}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SubsuperscriptBox["N", "lm", ""], 
    RowBox[{"(", "\[Omega]", ")"}], "-", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"\[Mu]", "+", 
       RowBox[{"\[Nu]", 
        SuperscriptBox["\[Lambda]", "4"]}]}], ")"}], 
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "lm", ""]}], "+", 
    SubsuperscriptBox["F", "lm", ""]}], ",", "     ", 
   RowBox[{"\[Lambda]", "=", 
    RowBox[{"l", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"ddfdcc71-85c4-4897-ac86-be3e1c3d1772"],

Cell["\<\
with N the spectral coefficients of \[Dash]J(\[Psi], \[Omega]+f). The linear \
part is diagonal (hence integrated exactly by an integrating factor or \
ETDRK4, Section 10); only N couples different modes.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e740e8b6-2ff3-42ca-85b3-a869ef741a34"],

Cell["9.3  The Coriolis coefficient and the \[Sqrt]3 normalisation", \
"Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"e804d5d8-d274-4c78-8745-4f14e4e70770"],

Cell["\<\
The planetary vorticity f = 2\[CapitalOmega] sin\[Phi] is a single spherical \
harmonic (l=1, m=0). Its spectral coefficient depends on the normalisation of \
the basis, and getting it wrong was the headline v5 bug. pyshtools uses REAL, \
4\[Pi]-normalised harmonics, in which\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5476ef35-7c23-4cca-b99a-bd4a13664b91"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["Y", "1", "0"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SqrtBox["3"], " ", "sin", "\[Phi]"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"98f2e85d-de2d-4813-91c5-efca92095e05"],

Cell["\<\
so to represent f = 2\[CapitalOmega] sin\[Phi] the required coefficient is c \
with c\[ThinSpace]\[Sqrt]3\[ThinSpace]sin\[Phi] = 2\[CapitalOmega] sin\[Phi], \
i.e.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"875a0481-3495-412d-8bc6-e8274301b8af"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["c", 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", "0"}], ""], "=", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"2", "\[CapitalOmega]"}], 
    SqrtBox["3"]], "     ", "\[LongRightArrow]", "     ", 
   RowBox[{"f", "(", "pole", ")"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"2", "\[CapitalOmega]"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"d6c3f3fd-4d5f-4ee4-b7de-b916884b2d19"],

Cell["\<\
The \[Beta]-effect that arrests the inverse cascade is \[Beta] \[Congruent] \
df/dy at the equator = 2\[CapitalOmega] on the unit sphere. (v5 used the \
unit-normalised coefficient 2\[CapitalOmega]\[Sqrt](4\[Pi]/3) with \
4\[Pi]-normalised harmonics, inflating f by \[Sqrt](4\[Pi]) \[TildeTilde] 3.5\
\[Times]; v6/v7 fix it. A spectral coefficient is meaningless until the basis \
normalisation is stated.)\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7b23ea0f-e9cf-465b-af38-349957456d3c"],

Cell["\<\
References: Vallis (2017), Atmospheric and Oceanic Fluid Dynamics, 2nd ed. \
(CUP); Charney, Fj\[OSlash]rtoft & von Neumann (1950) Tellus 2, 237.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"86f341b1-5c4b-4ef2-8f17-c674db6e7fb6"],

Cell["\<\
10.  Numerical Methods: Operator Splitting and Exponential Integrators\
\>", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"a9740e71-9260-4078-898d-225d01070e25"],

Cell["\<\
Improvements #3 and #4 (scientific_improvements.md \[Section]\[Section]3\
\[Dash]4). Split the vorticity equation into a stiff LINEAR part and a \
nonstiff NONLINEAR part:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7c345d99-5328-4f95-b857-50aede1663a9"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Omega]"}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "=", 
   RowBox[{"L", " ", "\[Omega]"}], "+", 
   RowBox[{"N", 
    RowBox[{"(", "\[Omega]", ")"}]}], ",", "     ", 
   RowBox[{"L", " ", "\[Omega]"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"-", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"\[Mu]", "+", 
       RowBox[{"\[Nu]", 
        SuperscriptBox["\[Lambda]", "4"]}]}], ")"}]}], "\[Omega]"}], ",", 
   "     ", 
   RowBox[{"N", 
    RowBox[{"(", "\[Omega]", ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", "J", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ",", "\[Omega]", "+", "f"}], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"15005214-8a7b-4f0e-9175-65da2cf3c803"],

Cell["\<\
L is DIAGONAL in spectral space (it just multiplies each mode by \
\[Dash](\[Mu]+\[Nu]\[Lambda]\.b3\.b3... )), so its exact flow exp(L\[Tau]) is \
known to machine precision \[Dash] no time-step restriction from the stiff \
hyperviscosity. The two schemes below differ only in how they combine this \
exact linear flow with an explicit treatment of N.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b78e34b6-c965-4638-8594-8943f293a535"],

Cell["10.1  Strang (2nd-order) operator splitting", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"303ac384-413d-4eee-90e6-d0c7eb5bf40e"],

Cell["\<\
v6 used a Lie\[Dash]Trotter split (exact linear factor \[SmallCircle] Heun \
advection), which is only FIRST-order globally \[Dash] a verified \
step-halving error ratio of 2.0, and ~10% of the energy leaking anomalously \
to hyperviscosity. Symmetrising the composition recovers 2nd order at \
essentially no cost:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3bac7e9a-f701-4d5f-9135-6bb10692f6ec"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"S", 
    RowBox[{"(", "dt", ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"L", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      FractionBox["dt", "2"], ")"}]}], "\[CenterDot]", 
    RowBox[{"N", 
     RowBox[{"(", "dt", ")"}]}], "\[CenterDot]", 
    RowBox[{"L", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      FractionBox["dt", "2"], ")"}]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",\

 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"47e94af6-58ff-46fa-aa9f-f1da8d671da0"],

Cell["\<\
half-step exact linear flow \[SmallCircle] full-step Heun (RK2) advection \
\[SmallCircle] half-step exact linear flow. By the \
Baker\[Dash]Campbell\[Dash]Hausdorff expansion the leading splitting error of \
the ASYMMETRIC Lie product L(dt)\[CenterDot]N(dt) is the commutator term\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b45ba9cc-62df-406a-9e61-348754488be6"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox["1", "2"], 
   SuperscriptBox["dt", "2"], 
   RowBox[{"[", "L", ",", "N", "]"}], "+", 
   RowBox[{"O", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     SuperscriptBox["dt", "3"], ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",\

 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"e07b062b-81d4-43e6-adb0-aad9b7fd14b0"],

Cell["\<\
\[Dash] first order globally. Symmetrising cancels that commutator, leaving \
\[Dash](dt\.b3/24)([L,[L,N]]+2[N,[L,N]]) + \[Ellipsis], i.e. local error O(dt\
\.b3), global O(dt\.b2). This tightens the energy/enstrophy budget and \
permits larger stable steps. TIME_SCHEME='strang' is the v7 default.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a6a7040f-f5cf-43fb-80a6-b718c775f01b"],

Cell["10.2  ETDRK4: exponential time differencing", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"defa16ad-eb83-4fa2-919f-f4887a6738a3"],

Cell["\<\
Because L is diagonal, an exponential integrator treats it EXACTLY while \
giving 4th-order accuracy on the nonlinear Jacobian (improvement #4). ETDRK4 \
(Cox & Matthews 2002; Kassam & Trefethen 2005) advances one step h=dt as four \
Jacobian evaluations:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d2867488-2eb0-44b0-89da-da256098166a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["N", "u", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"N", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["u", "n", ""], ")"}]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{"a", "=", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"E2", "\[CenterDot]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["u", "n", ""]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{"Q", "\[CenterDot]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["N", "u", ""]}]}], ",", "  ", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["N", "a", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"N", 
       RowBox[{"(", "a", ")"}]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{"b", "=", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"E2", "\[CenterDot]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["u", "n", ""]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{"Q", "\[CenterDot]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["N", "a", ""]}]}], ",", "  ", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["N", "b", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"N", 
       RowBox[{"(", "b", ")"}]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{"c", "=", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"E2", "\[CenterDot]", "a"}], "+", 
       RowBox[{"Q", "\[CenterDot]", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{
          RowBox[{"2", 
           SubsuperscriptBox["N", "b", ""]}], "-", 
          SubsuperscriptBox["N", "u", ""]}], ")"}]}]}], ",", "  ", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["N", "c", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"N", 
       RowBox[{"(", "c", ")"}]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["u", 
       RowBox[{"n", "+", "1"}], ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"E", "\[CenterDot]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["u", "n", ""]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{
        SubsuperscriptBox["N", "u", ""], 
        SubsuperscriptBox["f", "1", ""]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{"2", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{
          SubsuperscriptBox["N", "a", ""], "+", 
          SubsuperscriptBox["N", "b", ""]}], ")"}], 
        SubsuperscriptBox["f", "2", ""]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{
        SubsuperscriptBox["N", "c", ""], 
        SubsuperscriptBox["f", "3", ""]}]}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"626b0a5d-72bc-4202-a976-fd01b04af989"],

Cell["with the exact-linear coefficients (h=dt, z=hL per mode)", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a5248dce-97b2-4ad5-85f2-d0402288d4ea"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"E", "=", 
   SuperscriptBox["e", 
    RowBox[{"h", " ", "L"}]], ",", "   ", "E2", "=", 
   SuperscriptBox["e", 
    RowBox[{"h", " ", "L", "/", "2"}]], ",", "   ", "Q", "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["h", "2"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "1", ""], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"h", " ", "L", "/", "2"}], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"9826aff8-7fea-4083-8a77-8ec2d0422f4f"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["f", "1", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"h", " ", 
       RowBox[{"[", 
        RowBox[{"-", "4", "-", "z", "+", 
         RowBox[{
          SuperscriptBox["e", "z"], 
          RowBox[{"(", 
           RowBox[{"4", "-", "3", "z", "+", 
            SuperscriptBox["z", "2"]}], ")"}]}]}], "]"}], "/", 
       SuperscriptBox["z", "3"]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["f", "2", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"h", " ", 
       RowBox[{"[", 
        RowBox[{"2", "+", "z", "+", 
         RowBox[{
          SuperscriptBox["e", "z"], 
          RowBox[{"(", 
           RowBox[{"-", "2", "+", "z"}], ")"}]}]}], "]"}], "/", 
       SuperscriptBox["z", "3"]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["f", "3", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"h", " ", 
       RowBox[{"[", 
        RowBox[{"-", "4", "-", "3", "z", "-", 
         SuperscriptBox["z", "2"], "+", 
         RowBox[{
          SuperscriptBox["e", "z"], 
          RowBox[{"(", 
           RowBox[{"4", "-", "z"}], ")"}]}]}], "]"}], "/", 
       SuperscriptBox["z", "3"]}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"f11fe4ab-ebe8-4e70-8753-63f4f93dddef"],

Cell["\<\
When L\[RightArrow]0 the \[CurlyPhi]-functions reduce to E=E2=1 and the \
update collapses to classical RK4 \[Dash] ETDRK4 is the exact-linear analogue \
of RK4.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"765c3019-8125-41b2-8b0b-05bfc5f93d7c"],

Cell["10.3  The Kassam\[Dash]Trefethen contour integral", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"08bcbab9-ada5-4ab8-9773-3e2524c42bf9"],

Cell["\<\
Evaluated naively, the f_j quotients divide by z\.b3, and for our modes \
|z|=|L\[CenterDot]dt| \[LessTilde] 5\[Times]10\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \
\(-3\)]\) \[Dash] catastrophic cancellation (e\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(z\), \()\
\)\[Dash]1)/z \[Rule] 0/0 in floating point. Kassam & Trefethen (2005) \
average each \[CurlyPhi]-function over M points on a small circle around each \
eigenvalue, replacing the singular quotient by a well-conditioned Cauchy \
integral:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e789ff73-707c-4357-9606-05c118ead5a3"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "j", ""], 
   RowBox[{"(", "z", ")"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["1", 
     RowBox[{"2", "\[Pi]", " ", "\[ImaginaryI]"}]], 
    $CellContext`ContourIntegralBox[
     FractionBox[
      RowBox[{
        SubsuperscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "j", ""], 
        RowBox[{"(", "t", ")"}]}], 
      RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"(", 
          RowBox[{"t", "-", "z"}], ")"}]}]], "\[Gamma]"]}], "\[TildeEqual]", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["1", "M"], 
    UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     RowBox[{"k", "=", "1"}], "M"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "j", ""], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"z", "+", 
      SuperscriptBox["r", " "], 
      SuperscriptBox["e", 
       RowBox[{"\[ImaginaryI]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["\[Theta]", "k", ""]}]]}], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"285e649c-e5d9-44a7-8e98-8535258a1ce7"],

Cell["\<\
with the M=32 roots-of-unity contour (config_v7 ETDRK4_M=32). This removes \
the cancellation and makes the exact-linear treatment robust. ETDRK4 costs ~4 \
Jacobian evaluations per step vs Strang's 2 (~2\[Times] the cost) but is far \
more accurate on the stiff linear term \[Dash] worth it at higher resolution \
or longer dt (TIME_SCHEME='etdrk4').\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"77cc7f52-3c70-46e3-b1f5-204d1db614e9"],

Cell["\<\
References: Strang (1968) SIAM J. Numer. Anal. 5, 506; Cox & Matthews (2002) \
J. Comput. Phys. 176, 430; Kassam & Trefethen (2005) SIAM J. Sci. Comput. 26, \
1214; Ascher, Ruuth & Spiteri (1997) Appl. Numer. Math. 25, 151.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"b79a3590-c1e1-4f28-92bb-0134f71113c0"],

Cell["11.  Physically-Grounded Stochastic Forcing", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"7f898e16-10e6-403c-891d-4d408b78655a"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #5 (scientific_improvements.md \[Section]5). The forcing must \
inject a CONTROLLED energy rate \[Epsilon] in a chosen band, and optionally \
with a finite correlation time. config_v7 implements both.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"14b48b39-16a2-41d0-bcde-996e8ed96c95"],

Cell["11.1  Controlled energy-injection rate \[Epsilon]", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"37d59f30-3181-4748-af12-c566a22dad24"],

Cell["\<\
Each step adds an independent Gaussian increment \[Delta]\[Omega]_lm to every \
coefficient in the band [l_min, l_max], with per-coefficient standard \
deviation amp_l\[Sqrt]dt where amp_l = FORCE_AMP/\[Sqrt](l(l+1)). Because the \
increment is independent of the current field it adds enstrophy at rate amp_l\
\.b2 and energy at rate amp_l\.b2/(l(l+1)) per coefficient. Summing the \
(2l+1) real coefficients per degree gives the total energy-injection rate\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"138a4bac-7fe5-4e08-84b0-71d0227a5ca5"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"\[Epsilon]", "=", 
   RowBox[{
    UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     RowBox[{"l", "=", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["l", "min", ""]}], 
     SubsuperscriptBox["l", "max", ""]], 
    FractionBox[
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"2", "l", "+", "1"}], ")"}], 
      SuperscriptBox["amp", "l"], 
      SuperscriptBox[" ", "2"]}], 
     RowBox[{"l", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}]]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["FORCE_AMP", "2"], 
    UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     RowBox[{"l", "=", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["l", "min", ""]}], 
     SubsuperscriptBox["l", "max", ""]], 
    FractionBox[
     RowBox[{"2", "l", "+", "1"}], 
     SuperscriptBox[
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"l", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}], ")"}], "2"]]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"d82dd52c-e940-4ec3-bdc8-3987c94bb72d"],

Cell["\<\
So \[Epsilon] is fixed by the amplitude and band alone; inverting lets the \
code set FORCE_AMP = \[Sqrt](\[Epsilon]_target/S_band) from a TARGET rate \
rather than an arbitrary amplitude (config_v7 FORCE_FROM_EPSILON). \[Epsilon] \
matters because it fixes the frictional-arrest / jet-spacing scale k_fr ~ (\
\[Beta]\.b3/\[Epsilon])\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \(1/5\)]\) (Section 12).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fe15b466-9408-4e5d-8d0d-2fb14917ce2b"],

Cell["11.2  Ornstein\[Dash]Uhlenbeck coloured forcing", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"b9a952b9-044d-4fdc-985d-e1ddc7d89490"],

Cell["\<\
The 'white' branch is delta-correlated in time (a \[Sqrt]dt Wiener \
increment). The 'ou' branch instead evolves a persistent forcing field f_lm \
with a finite correlation time \[Tau]_c as the Ornstein\[Dash]Uhlenbeck \
process \[Dash] the unique stationary Gaussian Markov process:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8f19d34c-17eb-49de-b4e9-cb9deb6020e9"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"d", 
    SubsuperscriptBox["f", "lm", ""]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    FractionBox[
     SubsuperscriptBox["f", "lm", ""], 
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Tau]", "c", ""]], "dt"}], "+", 
   RowBox[{
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "l", ""], "dW"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"9c5a591a-c784-4763-9a47-41e8cf87aae0"],

Cell["Its stationary autocovariance is the exponential", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"374dacd2-a2a2-4673-8651-ca7fe7af840a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"C", 
    RowBox[{"(", "s", ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"\[LeftAngleBracket]", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"f", 
      RowBox[{"(", "t", ")"}]}], " ", 
     RowBox[{"f", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"t", "+", "s"}], ")"}]}]}], "\[RightAngleBracket]"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox[
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "l", ""], 
      SuperscriptBox[" ", "2"], 
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[Tau]", "c", ""]}], "2"], 
    SuperscriptBox["e", 
     RowBox[{"-", "\[LeftBracketingBar]", "s", "\[RightBracketingBar]", "/", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[Tau]", "c", ""]}]]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"67b74181-bd3a-48bc-a191-af70a6a24d5e"],

Cell["\<\
with stationary variance C(0)=\[Sigma]_l\.b2\[Tau]_c/2 and integral time \
\[Tau]_c. The code implements the EXACT AR(1) discretisation of this SDE. The \
amplitude \[Sigma]_l is fixed by demanding that as \[Tau]_c\[RightArrow]0 the \
OU tendency \[Delta]\[Omega]=f\[CenterDot]dt converge to the SAME white \
forcing (so \[Epsilon] is unchanged and the two branches are directly \
comparable): a tendency driven by a stationary process with \[Integral]C ds = \
amp_l\.b2 is white-equivalent, and for OU \[Integral]C ds = \[Sigma]_l\.b2\
\[Tau]_c\.b2, hence\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4fe9c9a3-fbc5-46a3-bd42-ec5abf5060e0"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "l", ""], 
   SuperscriptBox[" ", "2"], "=", 
   FractionBox[
    SuperscriptBox["amp", "l"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Tau]", "c", "2"]], "     ", "\[LongRightArrow]", 
   "     ", 
   RowBox[{"Var", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["f", "lm", ""], ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"C", 
    RowBox[{"(", "0", ")"}]}], "=", 
   FractionBox[
    SuperscriptBox["amp", "l"], 
    RowBox[{"2", " ", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Tau]", "c", ""]}]]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"ac8f830e-7d34-473c-b27a-9be8354f8605"],

Cell["\<\
The field is initialised at this stationary variance (no forcing transient). \
Coloured forcing removes the unphysical white-noise artefact and changes the \
injection statistics. In BOTH branches the forcing is added AFTER the \
deterministic Strang/ETDRK4 substep, so its \[Sqrt]dt scaling is preserved \
and it is never folded into the RK evaluations of N.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6cb39974-96e0-42ac-ab9f-6ea6b48fdb99"],

Cell["\<\
References: Maltrud & Vallis (1991) J. Fluid Mech. 228, 321; Constantinou, \
Farrell & Ioannou (2014) J. Atmos. Sci. 71, 1818.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"def2498a-2a7b-424b-9fdc-8c28c7048441"],

Cell["12.  Scale Analysis, Dealiasing and Cascade Diagnostics", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"de1abefb-280f-4bdb-b04c-203bdd025877"],

Cell["\<\
Improvements #1, #6, #8. Together these decide whether the model demonstrably \
produces jets and a dual cascade \[Dash] the project's stated goal.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"bb661893-4d81-461c-b9df-a3174c26fc68"],

Cell["12.1  The Rhines scale and the zonostrophy index", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"1f41cb1e-41e4-4e2f-9bae-644caca97c5a"],

Cell["\<\
Jets emerge when the inverse energy cascade runs from the forcing scale up to \
the Rhines scale and is halted there by \[Beta]. The Rhines wavenumber is \
where the eddy turnover rate matches the Rossby-wave frequency:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"542043e2-9c18-438e-bc99-1b00b6319898"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["l", "R", ""], "=", 
   SqrtBox[
    FractionBox[
     RowBox[{"2", "\[CapitalOmega]"}], "U"]], "     ", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"\[Beta]", "=", 
     RowBox[{"2", "\[CapitalOmega]"}], ",", " ", "R", "=", "1"}], ")"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"756f4627-607d-477e-952a-4dd92f493159"],

Cell["\<\
with U the rms large-scale velocity. Whether jets are SHARP is measured by \
the zonostrophy index (Galperin, Sukoriansky et al. 2006):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"cf9aa517-8da3-458a-aab2-2a0376b8fca4"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["R", "\[Beta]", ""], "=", 
   FractionBox[
    SubsuperscriptBox["k", "\[Beta]", ""], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["k", "R", ""]], ",", "     ", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["k", "\[Beta]", ""], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"(", 
     FractionBox[
      SuperscriptBox["\[Beta]", "3"], "\[Epsilon]"], ")"}], 
    RowBox[{"1", "/", "5"}]], ",", "     ", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["k", "R", ""], "=", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["l", "R", ""]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"f28f8073-8502-4233-8e1a-86ee0ccb423b"],

Cell["\<\
Regimes: R_\[Beta] \[GreaterTilde] 2.5 zonostrophic (sharp jets), \
1.5\[Dash]2.5 transitional, <1.5 friction-dominated (no jets). v6 forced at \
l_f\[TildeTilde]60\[Dash]80 with l_R\[TildeTilde]23 \[Dash] a separation of \
only 2.6, far too small, hence NO jets. v7 retunes to \[CapitalOmega]=6.5, \
forcing at l=100\[Dash]120, \[Mu]=0.01, giving the textbook ordering l_R(\
\[TildeTilde]10) < k_\[Beta](\[TildeTilde]26) < l_f(\[TildeTilde]110) and a \
design estimate R_\[Beta]\[TildeTilde]2.6 \[Dash] borderline zonostrophic. \
The energy balance that closes this is drag-dominated:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6ab2edf1-fcb1-4858-9080-6bf944b26e9b"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["E", "sat", ""], "=", 
   FractionBox["\[Epsilon]", 
    RowBox[{"2", "\[Mu]"}]], ",", "     ", "U", "=", 
   SqrtBox[
    FractionBox["\[Epsilon]", "\[Mu]"]]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",\

 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"c439b967-771a-477d-91d3-ae1077575326"],

Cell["\<\
These are design targets; they must be re-measured from a saturated run \
(improvement #2), which is why v7 spins up for \[GreaterEqual]5 drag times \
with an auto-stationarity guard (all of energy, enstrophy and zonal fraction \
must plateau to within 2% over a sliding window).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"362f1d79-d49b-4da3-a28b-808408c52387"],

Cell["12.2  Resolution and Orszag 2/3 dealiasing", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"cc0abc65-bed8-4471-903d-79ad901cf303"],

Cell["\<\
A wider inertial range needs higher truncation (improvement #6: v7 uses T170 \
vs v6's T127). The quadratic Jacobian generates modes up to 2L, which would \
alias back onto the resolved band unless removed. The Orszag (1971) 2/3 rule \
keeps only the lowest 2/3 of representable wavenumbers; pyshtools' Driscoll\
\[Dash]Healy DH2 grid OVERSAMPLES (2(L+1) latitudes \[Times] 2(L+1) \
longitudes for degree L), so quadratic products are dealiased at this \
truncation \[Dash] verified to 0.07% against a 2\[Times]-padded reference \
(Section 8).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f4af1043-b1b3-4112-9e46-dce49b07bd3f"],

Cell["12.3  Spectral flux \[Dash] the direct evidence for a cascade", \
"Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"f627faaa-043c-411f-8042-bb5dd87a341b"],

Cell["\<\
A broad spectrum is merely CONSISTENT with a dual cascade; it does not prove \
one. The rigorous diagnostic is the spectral FLUX computed from the nonlinear \
transfer T(l) (the projection of \[Dash]J(\[Psi],\[Omega]+f) onto each \
degree; verify_v7.spectral_flux). Since \[CapitalSigma]_l T(l)=0, the \
cumulative flux across degree l is\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2693d97c-a7f9-457d-949a-982124383f30"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[CapitalPi]", "E", ""], 
   RowBox[{"(", "l", ")"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["l", "'", ""], "=", "1"}], "l"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["T", "E", ""], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["l", "'", ""], ")"}]}], ",", "     ", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[CapitalPi]", "Z", ""], 
   RowBox[{"(", "l", ")"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["l", "'", ""], "=", "1"}], "l"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["T", "Z", ""], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["l", "'", ""], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"9e35eb1f-3546-4b8e-b556-d35da0f71c3b"],

Cell["\<\
\[CapitalPi]_E(l) is the net rate energy crosses from degrees \[LessEqual]l \
to degrees >l. The dual-cascade signature that PROVES an inverse cascade is:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4c5dd61d-79de-49c2-b99f-09051b0311b9"],

Cell["\<\
\[CapitalPi]_E(l) < 0 for l BELOW the forcing band \[Dash] energy flows \
UP-scale (toward small l): the inverse energy cascade.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"6656abba-c9d9-4f22-a980-4a81f4434f4b"],

Cell["\<\
\[CapitalPi]_Z(l) > 0 for l ABOVE the forcing band \[Dash] enstrophy flows \
DOWN-scale (toward large l): the forward enstrophy cascade.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"fb9665e5-63dd-4019-93fb-a2d52a83609b"],

Cell["\<\
This is the theory of Kraichnan (1967) / Batchelor: in 2-D the two quadratic \
invariants (energy and enstrophy) cannot both cascade the same way, so energy \
goes up and enstrophy goes down from the injection scale. Measuring the two \
flux SIGNS is what lets the project make a defensible claim about jets.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3191f381-3104-4c8e-b12d-fee017341da2"],

Cell["\<\
References: Rhines (1975) J. Fluid Mech. 69, 417; Vallis & Maltrud (1993) J. \
Phys. Oceanogr. 23, 1346; Galperin & Read (eds.), Zonal Jets (CUP 2019); \
Orszag (1971) J. Atmos. Sci. 28, 1074; Kraichnan (1967) Phys. Fluids 10, \
1417; Boffetta & Ecke (2012) Annu. Rev. Fluid Mech. 44, 427.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"77ea09b8-ccc9-43ec-9102-794efeddb5fb"],

Cell["13.  Spectral Vanishing Viscosity", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"f0d42397-574c-4f66-ad9a-19e9424ce2aa"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #7 (scientific_improvements.md \[Section]7). The \[Del]\[Cedilla] \
hyperviscosity absorbs ~10% of the ENERGY (it should drain mostly enstrophy). \
Spectral vanishing viscosity (Tadmor 1989) is a cleaner small-scale sink: \
identically zero over the resolved/inertial range, switching on smoothly only \
near truncation. Unlike a plain Laplacian it does not damp the large scales; \
unlike a sharp cutoff it is smooth (no Gibbs); and being a genuine modified \
viscosity it supplies the entropy dissipation that guarantees convergence to \
the correct weak solution. It acts as a Laplacian viscosity \
\[Dash]\[Epsilon]_SVV(l)\[CenterDot]\[Lambda]\[Omega] with an l-dependent \
coefficient (config_v7 SVV_*):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"dfd52063-a30a-4cce-8f7c-38f5acd254b6"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "SVV", ""], 
   RowBox[{"(", "l", ")"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "0", ""], "\[CenterDot]", 
    RowBox[{"exp", 
     RowBox[{"[", 
      RowBox[{"-", 
       SuperscriptBox[
        RowBox[{"(", 
         FractionBox[
          RowBox[{"L", "-", "l"}], 
          RowBox[{"l", "-", 
           SubsuperscriptBox["l", "cut", ""]}]], ")"}], "2"]}], "]"}]}]}], "     ", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"l", ">", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["l", "cut", ""]}], ")"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"0aa2afd0-917f-4a50-8db1-368fcac70e4e"],

Cell["\<\
and \[Epsilon]_SVV(l)=0 for l\[LessEqual]l_cut, with L=LMAX. The kernel is 0 \
at l_cut, rises smoothly, and reaches \[Epsilon]_0 at the truncation. The \
standard cutoff is l_cut ~ \[Sqrt]L (Maday & Tadmor 1989): \[Sqrt]170\
\[TildeTilde]13. Matching the hyperviscous cutoff rate \[Nu]\[Lambda]_max\!\(\
\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \(4\)]\)\[TildeTilde]4 fixes \
\[Epsilon]_0\[TildeTilde]4/(170\[CenterDot]171)\[TildeTilde]1.4\[Times]10\!\(\
\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \(-4\)]\). SVV can SUPPLEMENT \[Del]\[Cedilla] or, \
with NU_HYPER=0, REPLACE it as the sole small-scale sink.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d6eb94fe-2a22-4abc-a729-26db08915e2b"],

Cell["\<\
References: Tadmor (1989) SIAM J. Numer. Anal. 26, 30; Maday & Tadmor (1989) \
SIAM J. Numer. Anal. 26, 854; Jablonowski & Williamson (2011), in Numerical \
Techniques for Global Atmospheric Models (Springer).\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"b3f4de89-2ebe-452a-b8bf-f1e99f904d09"],

Cell["\<\
14.  Extended Barotropic Physics: Mean Flow, Topography, Deformation Radius\
\>", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"aa2f05ca-81b3-48e7-bdfb-30656265f4e3"],

Cell["\<\
Improvements #9\[Dash]#11 (scientific_improvements.md \[Section]\[Section]9\
\[Dash]11). Three OPTIONAL extra terms in the SAME barotropic solver, \
disabled by default so the base run is unchanged. Each adds genuine physics \
with a minimal code change.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c1f6e245-51c2-46a0-940d-d7fc115cc834"],

Cell["14.1  Differential-rotation mean flow (Newtonian relaxation)", \
"Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"8cc5ddc1-a65a-4e9b-9eb6-a5c6baea48df"],

Cell["\<\
The v6 cutaway's longitude 'shear' is a pure visualization twist, not \
dynamics. Instead relax the ZONAL-MEAN (m=0) vorticity toward a prescribed \
solar-like differential-rotation profile (Held\[Dash]Suarez 1994 core), so \
the mean shear is a real term that can go barotropically unstable and shed \
eddies. A fast-equator angular velocity\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ca225f16-b835-456d-ab23-0b23853c1abb"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[CapitalOmega]", 
    RowBox[{"(", "\[Phi]", ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "0", ""], "-", 
    RowBox[{"\[CapitalDelta]\[CapitalOmega]", " ", 
     SuperscriptBox["sin", "2"], "\[Phi]"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"42250f4f-751a-464c-a48b-28487a0b16cf"],

Cell["\<\
gives a zonal wind \!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(_\)]\)(\[Phi]) = \[Delta]\
\[CapitalOmega](\[Phi])\[CenterDot]R cos\[Phi] in the co-rotating frame (\
\[Delta]\[CapitalOmega]=\[Dash]\[CapitalDelta]\[CapitalOmega] sin\.b2\[Phi]); \
from \!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \
\(_\)]\)=\[Dash](1/R)\[PartialD]\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(\[Psi]\), \(_\)]\)/\
\[PartialD]\[Phi] the target streamfunction and vorticity are\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"02259453-82ac-49ed-a6d0-f9d6f470e88d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox["\[Psi]", "_"], "target", ""], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox[
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox["R", "2"], "\[CapitalDelta]\[CapitalOmega]"}], "3"], 
    SuperscriptBox["sin", "3"], "\[Phi]"}], ",", "     ", 
   SubsuperscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox["\[Omega]", "_"], "target", ""], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox["\[Psi]", "_"], "target", ""]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"323df2c7-745a-4f17-9093-16d5e9136a54"],

Cell["\<\
applied only to the m=0 modes (\[Del]\.b2 is diagonal, so \
\!\(\*SubscriptBox[OverscriptBox[\(\[Omega]\), \(_\)], \(target\)]\)_{l0} = \
\[Dash]l(l+1)\!\(\*SubscriptBox[OverscriptBox[\(\[Psi]\), \(_\)], \(target\)]\
\)_{l0}). The relaxation term (Held\[Dash]Suarez form) is\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ded5f956-352f-42a6-8d17-f50abe72fcec"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    RowBox[{
     FractionBox[
      RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", 
       OverscriptBox["\[Omega]", "_"]}], 
      RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "|"}], "relax"], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    FractionBox["1", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Tau]", "relax", ""]], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      OverscriptBox["\[Omega]", "_"], "-", 
      SubsuperscriptBox[
       OverscriptBox["\[Omega]", "_"], "target", ""]}], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"13adf7bd-a4a3-4bdf-8802-a551378bb62b"],

Cell["14.2  Topographic \[Beta] / bottom relief", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"56c22d76-7ddb-41b1-9e0e-b76ca0420bb8"],

Cell["\<\
Add a FIXED topography h(\[Theta],\[Phi]) to the potential vorticity, so the \
quantity advected by the flow becomes\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f3f54a17-9f00-49ba-87df-15b0db566f3d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"q", "=", "\[Omega]", "+", "f", "+", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{
     SubsuperscriptBox["f", "0", ""], "h"}], "H"], "\[Congruent]", "\[Omega]",
    "+", "f", "+", "\[Eta]"}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"450670c0-e093-45ce-a0fa-728c560a58d1"],

Cell["\<\
with the stationary topographic vorticity \[Eta](\[Theta],\[Phi]) = f_0 h/H. \
The tendency \[Dash]J(\[Psi],q) then splits as \[Dash]J(\[Psi],\[Omega]+f) \
\[Dash] J(\[Psi],\[Eta]): the ONLY change is an extra advection of the fixed \
field \[Eta] by the flow. \[Eta] is an external PV source, NOT flow \
vorticity, so the streamfunction inversion \[Psi]=\[Del]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\
\()\), \(-2\)]\)\[Omega] is unchanged. Physically the stationary PV-gradient \
\[Del]\[Eta] radiates topographic Rossby waves, exerts form drag, and can \
anchor standing eddies / lock jets \[Dash] breaking the artificial zonal \
symmetry. In the code \[Eta] is a few low-order harmonics (config_v7 \
TOPO_MODES, e.g. an l=2,m=0 belt + an l=3,m=2 ridge; only l\[GreaterEqual]1 \
is dynamical).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1838b676-b6aa-4422-ad08-9d0c67d7f4f4"],

Cell["14.3  Equivalent-barotropic model: finite deformation radius", \
"Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"b2b4e0d0-4c76-49ea-aaec-bce727bee06b"],

Cell["\<\
Promote the PV inversion to the free-surface / reduced-gravity form by adding \
one diagonal term, introducing an intrinsic length scale L_d (the Rossby \
radius of deformation):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ad8c0ba9-6463-46bf-8ac3-ee44194e16b2"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"q", "=", 
   SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "\[Psi]", "-", 
   FractionBox["\[Psi]", 
    SubsuperscriptBox["L", "d", "2"]], 
   RowBox[{"(", "+", "f", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"bb01c197-f8fd-4a96-a9bb-4c7a493abd57"],

Cell["\<\
The prognostic field is now the PV anomaly q; only the inversion changes,\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"02711070-66a5-4f47-8584-3a5b2b4804f0"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "lm", ""], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    FractionBox[
     SubsuperscriptBox["q", "lm", ""], 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"l", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}], "+", 
      RowBox[{"1", "/", 
       SubsuperscriptBox["L", "d", "2"]}]}]]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"55125e13-ceb2-4df8-841f-3f5df69c8708"],

Cell["\<\
(was \[Dash]q_lm/[l(l+1)]). With finite L_d the inverse cascade halts at L_d \
as well as at the Rhines scale, giving more realistic jet widths. \
DEFORMATION_RADIUS=None recovers the rigid-lid barotropic model \
byte-for-byte; L_d\[TildeTilde]0.2 (1/L_d\.b2=25, comparable to l(l+1) at l\
\[TildeTilde]4\[Dash]5) bites at planetary scales.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"64319682-c455-418b-b797-165ce817329d"],

Cell["\<\
References: Held & Suarez (1994) Bull. Amer. Meteorol. Soc. 75, 1825; Vallis \
& Maltrud (1993) J. Phys. Oceanogr. 23, 1346; Rhines (1975) J. Fluid Mech. \
69, 417; Vallis (2017) \[Section]\[Section]9, 14.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"49bc872a-6a55-46dc-bfc0-0e7208df793a"],

Cell["\<\
15.  Two-Layer Quasi-Geostrophic Model (Baroclinic Instability)\
\>", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"7a327841-ed0d-4b48-af45-86833bd54a84"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #12 (two_layer_qg.py). The minimal model in which jets arise \
SELF-CONSISTENTLY from an internal energy source \[Dash] baroclinic \
instability of an imposed vertical shear \[Dash] rather than from ad-hoc \
stochastic forcing. Two layers of resting depth H_1 (upper), H_2 (lower), \
coupled across a density interface (reduced gravity g' = g\[CapitalDelta]\
\[Rho]/\[Rho]). Each layer has a streamfunction \[Psi]_i and a QG potential \
vorticity:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e24a2c8a-6a02-4c22-810e-a7d20753e75c"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["q", "1", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], 
       SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "1", ""], "+", "f", "+", 
       RowBox[{
        SubsuperscriptBox["F", "1", ""], 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{
          SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "2", ""], "-", 
          SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "1", ""]}], ")"}]}]}], ",", "    ", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["F", "1", ""], "=", 
      FractionBox[
       SubsuperscriptBox["f", "0", "2"], 
       RowBox[{"g", "'", " ", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["H", "1", ""]}]]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["q", "2", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], 
       SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "2", ""], "+", "f", "+", 
       RowBox[{
        SubsuperscriptBox["F", "2", ""], 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{
          SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "1", ""], "-", 
          SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "2", ""]}], ")"}]}]}], ",", "    ", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["F", "2", ""], "=", 
      FractionBox[
       SubsuperscriptBox["f", "0", "2"], 
       RowBox[{"g", "'", " ", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["H", "2", ""]}]]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"53258249-8c9b-4fb8-887b-bf699075d828"],

Cell["\<\
The stretching terms F_i(\[Psi]_j\[Dash]\[Psi]_i) are vortex-stretching by \
the interface displacement. Each layer materially conserves its PV up to \
forcing/dissipation:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"532fcea8-4c31-40d3-9ba4-b1f4a1376b2b"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["q", "1", ""]}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{"J", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "1", ""], ",", 
         SubsuperscriptBox["q", "1", ""]}], ")"}]}], "=", "\[ScriptCapitalF]",
       "+", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalD]", "1", ""]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["q", "2", ""]}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{"J", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "2", ""], ",", 
         SubsuperscriptBox["q", "2", ""]}], ")"}]}], "=", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalD]", "2", ""]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"ae8bb0f4-b012-47e6-aaec-538e1747cc69"],

Cell["15.1  Imposed shear as the energy source", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"609dc6c4-b0f7-436e-a3ee-e8ba3dde1f0c"],

Cell["\<\
Split each field into a fixed background + perturbation. The background is \
solid-body rotation \!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(\[CapitalPsi]\), \(i\)]\) = \
\[Dash]U_i sin\[Phi] (a pure Y_10). Because \
\!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(\[CapitalPsi]\), \(i\)]\) \[Proportional] sin\[Phi], so \
is Q_i, and J(\!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(\[CapitalPsi]\), \
\(i\)]\),Q_i)=J(sin\[Phi],sin\[Phi])=0: the background is an EXACT steady \
solution for any U_1,U_2. The vertical shear U_1\[Dash]U_2 tilts the \
interface and stores available potential energy; perturbations tap it. The \
Charney\[Dash]Stern necessary condition for instability is that the \
meridional PV gradient dQ_i/d\[Phi] change sign between layers, which the \
F_i(U_i\[Dash]U_j) term arranges once the shear exceeds a \[Beta]-dependent \
critical value (Phillips 1954).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d52e58c1-7bee-4a47-9823-8a8ba9ee7d6c"],

Cell["15.2  Layer coupling: 2\[Times]2 PV inversion", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"f9b718ea-3719-4690-879c-1b90f6296ff9"],

Cell["\<\
With \[Del]\.b2\[RightArrow]\[Dash]\[Lambda], \[Lambda]=l(l+1), the \
perturbation inversion q = M\[Psi] is, per (l,m), a 2\[Times]2 system:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2f438303-a128-4703-a2a0-fbf4cea9f0de"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"M", "=", 
   RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
      {
       RowBox[{"-", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"\[Lambda]", "+", 
          SubsuperscriptBox["F", "1", ""]}], ")"}]}], 
       SubsuperscriptBox["F", "1", ""]},
      {
       SubsuperscriptBox["F", "2", ""], 
       RowBox[{"-", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"\[Lambda]", "+", 
          SubsuperscriptBox["F", "2", ""]}], ")"}]}]}
     }], ")"}], ",", "     ", 
   RowBox[{"det", " ", "M"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"\[Lambda]", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"\[Lambda]", "+", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["F", "1", ""], "+", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["F", "2", ""]}], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"d9a42ee7-349b-49ec-a502-cd108fe94aca"],

Cell["\<\
so \[Psi]=M\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \(-1\)]\)q per mode (det=0 only at \
l=0, the gauge, set to zero). The coupling k_d\.b2 \[Congruent] F_1+F_2 \
defines the internal deformation wavenumber. Energetically, total E = \
\[CapitalSigma]_i \.bd H_i\[Integral]|\[Del]\[Psi]_i|\.b2 + \.bd(f_0\.b2/g')\
\[Integral](\[Psi]_1\[Dash]\[Psi]_2)\.b2, the last term the APE; baroclinic \
instability converts mean APE \[Rule] eddy energy \[Rule] barotropic jets \
\[Dash] the signature is barotropic KE growing at the expense of the shear.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7f01debe-be81-461b-a13b-63a749832d7b"],

Cell["\<\
References: Phillips (1954) Tellus 6, 273; Panetta (1993) J. Atmos. Sci. 50, \
2073; Salmon, Lectures on Geophysical Fluid Dynamics (Oxford, 1998).\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"add9f225-2666-486f-b8bc-7f7b75fc604b"],

Cell["16.  Rotating Shallow-Water Equations on the Sphere", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"74a7ad16-b7da-48cc-8e35-d0f2c7101b26"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #13 (shallow_water.py). Advance from one non-divergent vorticity \
equation to the full shallow-water system, restoring horizontal DIVERGENCE, \
GRAVITY WAVES and GEOSTROPHIC ADJUSTMENT \[Dash] the next rung above \
barotropic. In vector-invariant form, for layer height h and velocity \
\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(\[RightVector]\)]\) on a unit sphere:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4ee729e1-5e25-4f5b-929b-edd1de7321e4"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "h"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[CenterDot]", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"h", " ", 
         OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], ")"}]}], "=", "0", "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", "mass", ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", 
        OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"f", "+", "\[Zeta]"}], ")"}], 
       OverscriptBox["z", "^"], "\[Cross]", 
       OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], "+", 
      RowBox[{"\[Del]", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"\[CapitalPhi]", "+", "K"}], ")"}]}], "=", 
      "\[ScriptCapitalD]", "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", "momentum", ")"}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"4be2c2c4-78b2-4917-bcc9-8ea05434832e"],

Cell["\<\
with geopotential \[CapitalPhi]=gh, kinetic energy \
K=\.bd|\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(\[RightVector]\)]\)|\.b2, relative \
vorticity \[Zeta]=\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(z\), \(^\)]\)\[CenterDot]\[Del]\
\[Cross]\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(\[RightVector]\)]\), and f=2\
\[CapitalOmega]sin\[Phi]. Taking \!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(z\), \(^\)]\)\
\[CenterDot]\[Del]\[Cross] and \[Del]\[CenterDot] of the momentum equation \
gives a closed system for the prognostic scalars vorticity \[Zeta], \
divergence \[Delta], and height h:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"bc8edc33-0b3d-46a9-8aea-4511e8d8b68d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Zeta]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "=", 
      RowBox[{"-", 
       RowBox[{"J", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ",", "\[Eta]"}], ")"}]}]}], "-", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Eta]"}], "\[CenterDot]", 
       RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Chi]"}]}], "-", 
      RowBox[{"\[Eta]", " ", "\[Delta]"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Delta]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"J", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"\[Eta]", ",", "\[Chi]"}], ")"}]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Eta]"}], "\[CenterDot]", 
        RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Psi]"}]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{"\[Eta]", " ", "\[Zeta]"}], "-", 
       RowBox[{
        SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"\[CapitalPhi]", "+", "K"}], ")"}]}]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "h"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "=", 
      RowBox[{"-", 
       RowBox[{"J", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ",", "h"}], ")"}]}], "-", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"\[Del]", "h"}], "\[CenterDot]", 
        RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Chi]"}]}], "-", 
       RowBox[{"h", " ", "\[Delta]"}]}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"85630452-d21f-4656-a635-f2c015881e24"],

Cell["\<\
with \[Eta]=\[Zeta]+f the absolute vorticity, and the velocity recovered by \
the Helmholtz decomposition \[Psi]=\[Del]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \
\(-2\)]\)\[Zeta], \[Chi]=\[Del]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \(-2\)]\)\[Delta], \
\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(\[RightVector]\)]\)=\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(z\), \
\(^\)]\)\[Cross]\[Del]\[Psi]+\[Del]\[Chi]. In the NON-DIVERGENT limit (\
\[Delta]=\[Chi]=0) the vorticity equation collapses to \[PartialD]\[Zeta]/\
\[PartialD]t=\[Dash]J(\[Psi],\[Zeta]+f) \[Dash] the barotropic model, which \
the code checks. The \[Dash]\[Del]\.b2\[CapitalPhi] term and the \[Dash]h\
\[Delta] mass term are the two sides of the gravity-wave / \
geostrophic-adjustment mechanism absent from barotropic.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9ca46881-b94d-4d6a-a5e1-78151652a387"],

Cell["\<\
Verification uses Williamson et al. (1992) test case 2 \[Dash] global steady \
solid-body rotation, an exact time-independent solution (gradient-wind \
balance) for which all three tendencies must vanish to truncation error.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"17549d59-e93f-45fb-9c08-8caffb1d8874"],

Cell["\<\
References: Williamson et al. (1992) J. Comput. Phys. 102, 211; Galewsky, \
Scott & Polvani (2004) Tellus A 56, 429; Bourke (1972) Mon. Wea. Rev. 100, \
683.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"1337c872-a4d2-4543-8d24-0c5317a90c3c"],

Cell["17.  Two-Dimensional Magnetohydrodynamics (Barotropic MHD)", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"df784cce-a103-408c-bb37-1e673186482b"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #14 (mhd_barotropic.py). Add a magnetic field and the Lorentz \
force \[Dash] the physically correct direction for the SOLAR framing, since \
in the tachocline a toroidal field suppresses the inverse cascade and can \
quench or reorganise jets. In 2-D both the velocity and the magnetic field \
derive from scalar potentials:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"23c21d5f-db21-4535-99fd-8339f96795d1"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox["z", "^"], "\[Cross]", 
    RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Psi]"}]}], ",", "     ", "\[Omega]", "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "\[Psi]"}], ";", "        ", 
   OverscriptBox["B", "\[RightVector]"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox["z", "^"], "\[Cross]", "\[Del]", "A"}], ",", "     ", "j", "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "A"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"9f42afa3-63a6-4db0-9752-8c2a7b726390"],

Cell["\<\
where A is the magnetic flux function and j the out-of-plane current density \
(units \[Rho]=\[Mu]_0=1). The incompressible MHD equations reduce to TWO \
coupled advection equations \[Dash] a vorticity equation with a Lorentz \
tension, and an induction equation for A:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"dd332db2-9ead-436f-b337-31fbe2b79182"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Omega]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{"J", 
       RowBox[{"(", "\[Psi]", ",", 
        RowBox[{"\[Omega]", "+", "f"}], ")"}]}], "=", 
      RowBox[{"J", 
       RowBox[{"(", "A", ",", "j", ")"}]}], "+", "\[Nu]", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "\[Omega]"}], "+", "F", "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", "vorticity", ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "A"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{"J", 
       RowBox[{"(", "\[Psi]", ",", "A", ")"}]}], "=", 
      RowBox[{"\[Eta]", " ", 
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "A"}], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", "induction", ")"}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"9151e174-151e-4585-8010-4f8de56cd0c9"],

Cell["\<\
with f=2\[CapitalOmega]sin\[Phi], \[Nu] the (hyper)viscosity, \[Eta] the \
magnetic diffusivity. BOTH the advection J(\[Psi],\[CenterDot]) and the \
Lorentz tension J(A,j) use the SAME spherical Jacobian primitive \[Dash] the \
magnetic tension is the Jacobian of the flux function with the current, \
exactly analogous to vorticity advection. (Sign convention: the \
self-consistent choice is j=\[Del]\.b2A with tension \
+J(A,j)=+J(A,\[Del]\.b2A), which gives \[Sigma]\.b2=+(k\[CenterDot]v_A)\.b2>0 \
\[Dash] restoring Alfv\[EAcute]n waves, not a spurious instability.)\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"490692f7-1763-4914-b752-2078ce724425"],

Cell["17.1  Ideal invariants and Alfv\[EAcute]n waves", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"7ecef1a9-df3c-4816-8065-5f604749a68d"],

Cell["\<\
In the ideal limit (\[Nu]=\[Eta]=F=0) 2-D MHD conserves three quadratic \
invariants, all checked by the code:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"161364ce-c001-4b79-812e-d3dbb2bb2c3a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{"E", "=", 
      RowBox[{
       FractionBox["1", "2"], "\[Integral]", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
          OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], 
          SuperscriptBox["\[RightBracketingBar]", "2"]}], "+", 
         RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
          OverscriptBox["B", "\[RightVector]"], 
          SuperscriptBox["\[RightBracketingBar]", "2"]}]}], ")"}], 
       "d\[CapitalOmega]"}], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       FractionBox["1", "2"], 
       UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", "lm", ""], "\[Lambda]", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         SuperscriptBox[
          SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "lm", ""], "2"], "+", 
         SuperscriptBox[
          SubsuperscriptBox["A", "lm", ""], "2"]}], ")"}]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"\[LeftAngleBracket]", 
       SuperscriptBox["A", "2"], "\[RightAngleBracket]"}], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", "lm", ""], 
       SuperscriptBox[
        SubsuperscriptBox["A", "lm", ""], "2"]}], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"mean", "-", "square", " ", "flux"}], ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["H", "c", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"\[Integral]", 
       OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", 
       OverscriptBox["B", "\[RightVector]"], "d\[CapitalOmega]"}], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", "lm", ""], "\[Lambda]", 
       SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "lm", ""], 
       SubsuperscriptBox["A", "lm", ""]}], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"cross", "-", "helicity"}], ")"}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"f01201c8-ed2a-4296-840c-67906a29628b"],

Cell["\<\
Linearising the ideal equations about a background field B_0 gives transverse \
oscillations at the Alfv\[EAcute]n frequency\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"bb0ae105-0b64-4c76-a497-dea45bfe302c"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "A", ""], "=", 
   RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
    RowBox[{
     OverscriptBox["k", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", 
     OverscriptBox[
      SubscriptBox["v", "A"], "\[RightVector]"]}], "\[RightBracketingBar]"}], 
   ",", "     ", 
   OverscriptBox[
    SubscriptBox["v", "A"], "\[RightVector]"], "=", 
   OverscriptBox[
    SubscriptBox["B", "0"], "\[RightVector]"], "    ", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"\[Rho]", "=", "1"}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",\

 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"9ef04e26-27fd-4368-ab06-a7598918d273"],

Cell["\<\
\[Omega]_A \[Proportional] |B_0| and \[Omega]_A \[Proportional] k \[Dash] the \
defining dispersion of Alfv\[EAcute]n waves. The code verifies the four \
robust signatures: the perturbation OSCILLATES (bounded, not growing); \
kinetic and magnetic energy EXCHANGE periodically at fixed total; the \
frequency scales LINEARLY with field strength; and with the perturbation \
wavenumber.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"58eec8c1-bcce-4b96-971e-4e05a8ef592f"],

Cell["\<\
References: Biskamp (2003), Magnetohydrodynamic Turbulence (CUP); Tobias, \
Diamond & Hughes (2007) ApJ 667, L113; Gilman (2000) ApJ 544, L79 \
(shallow-water MHD).\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"399c139c-e3a2-41ce-968d-8dd5fdfe1e61"],

Cell["\<\
18.  Boussinesq Rayleigh\[Dash]B\[EAcute]nard Convection in a Rotating Shell\
\>", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"2fac63ee-403a-43a8-84a7-66b1c2961235"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #15 (boussinesq_shell.py). The MINIMAL TRUE convection model. \
Where improvements #1\[Dash]#14 all evolve a single 2-D scalar with NO \
buoyancy, this adds the three ingredients that make the problem convection: a \
temperature perturbation \[CapitalTheta] with its own evolution equation, a \
BUOYANCY FORCE driving the flow, and a vertical velocity (a 3-D \
poloidal/toroidal field). Governing equations in a shell r_i<r<r_o, gravity \
\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(g\), \(\[RightVector]\)]\)=\[Dash]g\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\
\(r\), \(^\)]\), rotation \[CapitalOmega]\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(z\), \(^\)]\), \
with control numbers Ra (Rayleigh), Ek (Ekman), Pr (Prandtl):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4a971427-0e3d-415d-86d6-1d24062d8adf"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[CapitalTheta]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{
       OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", "\[Del]", 
       "\[CapitalTheta]"}], "=", 
      RowBox[{"\[Kappa]", 
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "\[CapitalTheta]"}], "+", 
      RowBox[{"S", 
       RowBox[{"(", "r", ")"}]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Omega]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", "\[Del]"}], 
        ")"}], "\[Omega]"}], "-", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         OverscriptBox["\[Omega]", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", 
         "\[Del]"}], ")"}], 
       OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], "=", 
      RowBox[{"-", 
       FractionBox[
        RowBox[{"2", "\[CapitalOmega]"}], "Ek"], 
       FractionBox[
        RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", 
         OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], 
        RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "z"}]]}], "+", 
      RowBox[{"Ra", " ", "Pr", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         OverscriptBox["r", "^"], "\[Cross]", "\[Del]", "\[CapitalTheta]"}], 
        ")"}]}], "+", 
      RowBox[{"Pr", " ", 
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "\[Omega]"}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"ad170eed-1d5b-4909-8fbe-9a437a84a9ce"],

Cell["\<\
The buoyancy term Ra\[CenterDot]Pr\[CenterDot](\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(r\), \(^\
\)]\)\[Cross]\[Del]\[CapitalTheta]) is the curl of the buoyancy force \[Rho]'\
\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(g\), \
\(\[RightVector]\)]\)\[Proportional]\[CapitalTheta]\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(r\), \
\(^\)]\); the (2\[CapitalOmega]/Ek)\[PartialD]\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(\
\[RightVector]\)]\)/\[PartialD]z term is the curl of the Coriolis force. S(r) \
= \[Dash]w\[ThinSpace]d\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(T\), \(_\)]\)/dr is the \
background heating.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a3c60b10-0359-4205-86f3-b47054d39d09"],

Cell["18.1  Linear onset \[Dash] the Chandrasekhar eigenvalue problem", \
"Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"1fe85d3d-da9a-42c4-b467-be4b7f15630d"],

Cell["\<\
Linearising about rest and projecting on a horizontal planform of wavenumber \
a, the marginal-stability amplitudes of vertical velocity W, vertical \
vorticity \[Zeta] and temperature \[CapitalTheta] obey (Chandrasekhar 1961, \
D=d/dz, Ta=Ek\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \(-2\)]\) the Taylor number):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9be94318-69f3-4434-b3cf-8c6712529992"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox[
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         SuperscriptBox["D", "2"], "-", 
         SuperscriptBox["a", "2"]}], ")"}], "2"], "W", "=", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["a", "2"], " ", "Ra", " ", "\[CapitalTheta]"}], "-", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["Ta", 
        RowBox[{"1", "/", "2"}]], "D", "\[Zeta]"}], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"vertical", " ", "momentum"}], ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{
        SuperscriptBox["D", "2"], "-", 
        SuperscriptBox["a", "2"]}], ")"}], "\[Zeta]", "=", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["Ta", 
        RowBox[{"1", "/", "2"}]], "D", "W"}], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"vertical", " ", "vorticity"}], ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{
        SuperscriptBox["D", "2"], "-", 
        SuperscriptBox["a", "2"]}], ")"}], "\[CapitalTheta]", "=", 
      RowBox[{"-", "W"}], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", "heat", ")"}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"e4ae9052-1830-4585-96f9-fbda02d44232"],

Cell["\<\
Eliminating \[Zeta] and \[CapitalTheta] gives the sixth-order scalar \
eigenvalue problem whose lowest eigenvalue over the planform a is the \
critical Rayleigh number Ra_c:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"52fa8cfd-dc46-47d3-a16d-ac1480718ad6"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["D", "2"], "-", 
       SuperscriptBox["a", "2"]}], ")"}], "3"], "W"}], "+", 
   RowBox[{"Ta", " ", 
    SuperscriptBox["D", "2"], "W"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    SuperscriptBox["a", "2"], "Ra", " ", "W"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"0ea9358f-d590-4adc-bbdc-a92e2f26f341"],

Cell["\<\
With fixed-temperature plates, the mechanical boundary conditions fix the \
classic benchmarks (solved by Chebyshev collocation, N\[TildeTilde]40 \
collocation points, to machine accuracy):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ab4459e6-3ba4-4c62-bce1-1a8d930f8f1e"],

Cell["\<\
Stress-free (\"free\"): W=D\.b2W=0, D\[Zeta]=0 \[LongRightArrow] Ra_c = 27\
\[Pi]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \(4\)]\)/4 = 657.511 (Ta=0).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c469bd71-68cf-4afc-9579-78d456414062"],

Cell["No-slip (\"rigid\"): W=DW=0, \[Zeta]=0 \[LongRightArrow] Ra_c = \
1707.762 (Ta=0).", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"04e1b26b-f43b-4040-b46e-\
5d0e88121470"],

Cell["\<\
Rapid rotation: Ra_c \[Proportional] Ek\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \
\(-4/3\)]\) \[Dash] rotation strongly stabilises convection and selects a \
narrow (a\[Proportional]Ek\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \(-1/3\)]\)) cell, the \
onset of the columnar (banana-cell) regime of Section 3.2.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"e70378c0-8e02-40f3-bc71-ac62eb6a7889"],

Cell["\<\
The convective NONLINEARITY is verified separately via the Saltzman (1962) / \
Lorenz (1963) Galerkin truncation \[Dash] the smallest self-contained system \
carrying the advective nonlinearity + buoyancy exchange \[Dash] which \
conserves energy in the dissipationless limit.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c895eff6-81d2-4e04-8247-d8c00261c1c7"],

Cell["\<\
References: Chandrasekhar (1961), Hydrodynamic and Hydromagnetic Stability \
(Oxford); Christensen & Aubert (2006) Geophys. J. Int. 166, 97; Gastine, \
Wicht & Aurnou (2013) Icarus 225, 156; Saltzman (1962) J. Atmos. Sci. 19, \
329; Lorenz (1963) J. Atmos. Sci. 20, 130.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"de59dca0-cd55-4ef8-af9f-df60527b4961"],

Cell["19.  Anelastic Convection in a Stratified Shell", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"04b3f61a-e0b7-4fbe-93e9-0029cbc78781"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #16 (anelastic_shell.py). Boussinesq treats the background \
density as uniform \[Dash] valid only for a thin layer. The solar convection \
zone spans ~14 density scale heights (\[Rho] varies by \
~10\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(0\), \(6\)]\) from base to photosphere), so \
Boussinesq is INVALID there. The anelastic approximation (Gough 1969; \
Braginsky & Roberts 1995) filters sound waves while retaining the strongly \
varying background density \!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(\[Rho]\), \(_\)]\)(r). Its \
two defining consequences:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"477672d1-c3b2-4b9d-8994-da06361d8a2c"],

Cell["19.1  The anelastic mass constraint", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"d6c06758-4803-4931-a7a3-efd9323381e0"],

Cell["\<\
Continuity becomes a constraint on the MASS flux, not the velocity:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9c32d512-671b-4601-a218-80a55757e0f4"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[CenterDot]", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"], 
      OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], ")"}]}], "=", "0", "     ", "\[LongRightArrow]",
    "     ", 
   RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[CenterDot]", 
    OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", "\[Del]", 
    RowBox[{"ln", " ", 
     OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"]}]}], "\[NotEqual]", "0"}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"4a898a76-41c6-4bb9-9038-756091c97b6a"],

Cell["\<\
so the velocity itself is COMPRESSIBLE \[Dash] this is what produces the \
up/down-flow ASYMMETRY of stratified convection: broad slow upflows, narrow \
fast downdrafts. The constraint is enforced exactly by writing the mass flux \
(not the velocity) with poloidal/toroidal scalars,\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d9e6b901-d88d-454d-ab30-b18cc812c3e6"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"], 
    OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Cross]", 
     RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Cross]"}]}], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"P", " ", 
      OverscriptBox["r", "^"]}], ")"}]}], "+", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Cross]"}], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"T", " ", 
      OverscriptBox["r", "^"]}], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"40519d6b-ad2e-4090-9c2e-3b31c7cfe13c"],

Cell["\<\
which makes \[Del]\[CenterDot](\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(\[Rho]\), \
\(_\)]\)\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(\[RightVector]\)]\)) = \
\[Del]\[CenterDot](\[Del]\[Cross]\[CenterDot]) \[Congruent] 0 identically \
(verified to machine precision).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"bfe5c2c1-720d-4e6c-8310-8a699acdedd2"],

Cell["19.2  The polytropic reference state", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"a55dbbf5-c31b-4605-889c-8c683c265f65"],

Cell["\<\
The background is a hydrostatic polytrope over N_\[Rho] density scale heights \
(Jones et al. 2011 anelastic benchmark). With aspect ratio \[Eta]=r_i/r_o, \
polytropic index n, gravity g\[Proportional]1/r\.b2, the dimensionless \
temperature \[Zeta](r) is linear in 1/r and the background fields are its \
powers:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d373528e-567b-41a2-b2fc-4b62b5d1b4b0"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[Zeta]", 
    RowBox[{"(", "r", ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SubsuperscriptBox["c", "0", ""], "+", 
    RowBox[{
     SubsuperscriptBox["c", "1", ""], 
     FractionBox["d", "r"]}]}], ",", "        ", 
   OverscriptBox["T", "_"], "=", "\[Zeta]", ",", "     ", 
   OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox["\[Zeta]", "n"], ",", "     ", 
   OverscriptBox["p", "_"], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox["\[Zeta]", 
    RowBox[{"n", "+", "1"}]]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"51376f8f-7dcf-438f-9945-317db6c2b7ff"],

Cell["\<\
(d=r_o\[Dash]r_i; ideal gas \!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(p\), \
\(_\)]\)=\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(\[Rho]\), \(_\)]\)\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(T\), \
\(_\)]\) automatically). Then the number of density scale heights is exactly\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"76f4d690-9553-4718-9121-6ed2fed34a60"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["N", "\[Rho]", ""], "=", 
   RowBox[{"ln", 
    RowBox[{"[", 
     FractionBox[
      RowBox[{
       OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"], 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["r", "i", ""], ")"}]}], 
      RowBox[{
       OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"], 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["r", "o", ""], ")"}]}]], "]"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"5a4941ff-643b-4b83-9985-4f74ddf3e67d"],

Cell["\<\
and hydrostatic balance d\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(p\), \(_\)]\)/dr = \[Dash]\!\(\
\*OverscriptBox[\(\[Rho]\), \(_\)]\)\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(g\), \(_\)]\) \
holds. The polytrope is p\[Proportional]\[Rho]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \
\((n+1)/n\)]\); it is exactly ISENTROPIC when n=n_ad=1/(\[Gamma]\[Dash]1) and \
SUPER-adiabatic (convectively unstable, d\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(s\), \
\(_\)]\)/dr<0) when n<n_ad \[Dash] the physical regime for convection.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0842c9b8-dc08-4d7c-a500-ca78b7f6abfa"],

Cell["\<\
References: Gough (1969) J. Atmos. Sci. 26, 448; Braginsky & Roberts (1995) \
GAFD 79, 1; Jones et al. (2011) Icarus 216, 120; Lantz & Fan (1999) ApJS 121, \
247.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"9a4ef338-0acb-4b51-b5ba-94c819ce997c"],

Cell["20.  Community Solvers: Rayleigh and Dedalus", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"e1f5213d-270c-4a43-a1df-6c762b61c569"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #17 (rayleigh_dedalus_setup.py). Rather than hand-build a 3-D \
convection solver (years of development + verification risk), map the control \
parameters onto a VALIDATED community code: Rayleigh (Featherstone & Hindman \
2016, a pseudo-spectral anelastic convection/dynamo code) or Dedalus (Burns \
et al. 2020, a general spectral-PDE framework whose spherical bases express \
the shell system in a few dozen lines). The module emits ready-to-run input \
for either code from a single parameter object, with the SAME physics in \
both. The shared nondimensional convention:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"375eb9c9-2b77-4e57-9b30-e3bab28a1044"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{"Ra", "=", 
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[Alpha]", " ", "g", " ", "\[CapitalDelta]T", " ", 
        SuperscriptBox["d", "3"]}], 
       RowBox[{"\[Nu]", " ", "\[Kappa]"}]], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"buoyancy", " ", 
        RowBox[{"vs", "."}], " ", "diffusion"}], ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{"Ek", "=", 
      FractionBox["\[Nu]", 
       RowBox[{"2", "\[CapitalOmega]", " ", 
        SuperscriptBox["d", "2"]}]], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"viscosity", " ", 
        RowBox[{"vs", "."}], " ", "rotation"}], ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{"Pr", "=", 
      FractionBox["\[Nu]", "\[Kappa]"], ",", "     ", "Pm", "=", 
      FractionBox["\[Nu]", "\[Eta]"], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"thermal", ",", " ", "magnetic", " ", "Prandtl"}], ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{"\[Eta]", "=", 
      FractionBox[
       SubsuperscriptBox["r", "i", ""], 
       SubsuperscriptBox["r", "o", ""]], ",", "     ", "d", "=", 
      RowBox[{
       SubsuperscriptBox["r", "o", ""], "-", 
       SubsuperscriptBox["r", "i", ""]}], "=", "1", "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"aspect", " ", "ratio"}], ")"}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"2e5567e8-9e9c-4d66-8d33-a08c802dd3a5"],

Cell["\<\
reference_type=1 is a Boussinesq shell (improvement #15); reference_type=2 is \
a polytropic anelastic shell (improvement #16) parameterised by N_\[Rho] and \
n. The module verifies that the Rayleigh namelist round-trips through a \
bundled parser (every control number reads back exactly), that the Dedalus \
script is valid Python whose parameter block exec's to the requested values, \
and that the Boussinesq\[LeftRightArrow]anelastic and \
no-slip\[LeftRightArrow]stress-free toggles propagate to both.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e47b01b4-871f-4fd6-8e14-50dbfc51a296"],

Cell["\<\
References: Featherstone & Hindman (2016) ApJ 818, 32 (Rayleigh); Burns, \
Vasil, Oishi, Lecoanet & Brown (2020) Phys. Rev. Research 2, 023068 \
(Dedalus); Christensen et al. (2001) Phys. Earth Planet. Inter. 128, 25 \
(dynamo benchmark).\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"1323a4d4-2b67-4ba3-87d0-21d9ef326d1f"],

Cell["21.  Coupling to the Model S Solar Stratification", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"14a17333-01fc-47e0-bfdb-0fb68dc902fc"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #18 (model_s_stratification.py). Drive the convection of #15\
\[Dash]#17 with a REALISTIC solar background \[Dash] temperature, density, \
gravity and entropy vs. radius from a standard solar model \[Dash] rather \
than a constant or ad-hoc profile. The convective length scales, velocities \
and super-adiabaticity are all set by the true stratification, so Model S \
makes a simulation quantitatively comparable to helioseismology (0.713 \
\[LessEqual] r/R_\[CircleDot] \[LessEqual] 1.0). Gravity is not tabulated \
\[Dash] the CZ holds \[LessTilde]2% of the Sun's mass, so to ~1%\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7d96cb34-5ac4-44b9-becd-7e796140db39"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"g", 
    RowBox[{"(", "r", ")"}]}], "=", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"G", " ", 
     SubscriptBox["M", "\[CircleDot]"]}], 
    SuperscriptBox["r", "2"]], ",", "     ", 
   RowBox[{"g", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"r", "=", 
      SubscriptBox["R", "\[CircleDot]"]}], ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"274", " ", 
    RowBox[{"m", " ", 
     SuperscriptBox["s", 
      RowBox[{"-", "2"}]]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"6c0fb95c-9c20-4f29-a194-4bca59ada17b"],

Cell["\<\
The bulk convection zone is nearly ISENTROPIC: the logarithmic gradient \
matches the adiabatic value,\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9b0a1746-7a2f-4854-b57a-dc1418baa030"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"\[Del]", "=", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"d", " ", 
     RowBox[{"ln", " ", "T"}]}], 
    RowBox[{"d", " ", 
     RowBox[{"ln", " ", "P"}]}]], "\[TildeTilde]", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "ad", ""], "=", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[Gamma]", "-", "1"}], "\[Gamma]"], "=", "0.4", "     ", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"\[Gamma]", "=", 
     RowBox[{"5", "/", "3"}]}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"f69f3190-9ab2-489a-93b5-d029eae5d291"],

Cell["\<\
so d\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(s\), \(_\)]\)/dr\[TildeTilde]0 with only a slight \
super-adiabatic deficit \[Dash] the small excess that actually drives the \
convection \[Dash] departing only in the thin radiative surface layer. Anchor \
values the profile reproduces (Model S / standard solar model):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5590a76e-f7a5-4855-a8fa-51e5f7c6daff"],

Cell["\<\
Base of CZ (x=0.713): T\[TildeTilde]2.18\[Times]10\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(0\), \
\(6\)]\) K, \[Rho]\[TildeTilde]0.187 g cm\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \
\(-3\)]\), g\[TildeTilde]539 m s\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \(-2\)]\).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"7618d00b-ad97-421a-8929-909d7d3c0b6f"],

Cell["\<\
Photosphere (x=1.0): T\[TildeTilde]5.77\[Times]10\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(0\), \
\(3\)]\) K, \[Rho]\[TildeTilde]2.5\[Times]10\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \
\(-7\)]\) g cm\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \(-3\)]\), g\[TildeTilde]274 m \
s\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\), \(-2\)]\).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"a4baf2f5-eb4f-419a-b55b-20b70ed12208"],

Cell["\<\
Density scale heights across the CZ: ln[\!\(\*SubscriptBox[OverscriptBox[\(\
\[Rho]\), \(_\)], \(base\)]\)/\!\(\*SubscriptBox[OverscriptBox[\(\[Rho]\), \
\(_\)], \(top\)]\)] \[TildeTilde] 13.5 \[Dash] the deep, highly stratified \
envelope that makes the ANELASTIC model (#16), not Boussinesq, the correct \
reduced description.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"e7af15e0-6ed6-4b1d-bbd8-d08ab7b6f91b"],

Cell["\<\
Honesty: this is a smooth fit to Model S anchored to published values, not \
the Model S data file itself; the thin surface ionization layers are \
approximate. For quantitative work, replace the bundled table with actual \
Model S / MESA output \[Dash] the interpolant API is unchanged.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4e26067b-86bb-4306-b5e9-b043cb119914"],

Cell["\<\
References: Christensen-Dalsgaard et al. (1996) Science 272, 1286 (Model S); \
Miesch (2005) Living Rev. Solar Phys. 2, 1; Stix, The Sun (2nd ed., 2002).\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"b17241d6-b9db-49df-88b1-11ea3320b081"],

Cell["22.  Lagrangian Transport and Finite-Time Lyapunov Exponents", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"f82b69b1-0501-438c-beb4-4f93100dd709"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #19 (lagrangian_ftle.py). A snapshot of vorticity is an EULERIAN \
object; it cannot say where fluid is stirred versus transported coherently. \
Advecting passive tracers with the (verified-correct) velocity field and \
computing FTLE extracts the Lagrangian coherent structures \[Dash] the \
material transport BARRIERS. On a rotating sphere the zonal JETS are exactly \
such barriers: fluid does not cross a jet core, so an FTLE ridge sits on each \
jet while the flanks mix. This turns the movie into evidence about transport.\
\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"48ab61e9-4674-496a-8f07-65f14be1f1d5"],

Cell["22.1  The tracer equation", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"329cdb36-04ed-48fc-a0b4-adbb6205d5a0"],

Cell["\<\
With \[Psi]_lm=\[Dash]\[Omega]_lm/[l(l+1)] and \!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(u\), \(\
\[RightVector]\)]\)=\!\(\*OverscriptBox[\(z\), \(^\)]\)\[Cross]\[Del]\[Psi], \
the colatitude/longitude velocity components (unit sphere) and the tracer ODE \
are\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"74560136-90c2-48a2-981b-9c6d55fae395"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["u", "\[Theta]"], "=", 
      RowBox[{"-", 
       FractionBox["1", 
        RowBox[{"sin", "\[Theta]"}]], 
       FractionBox[
        RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Psi]"}], 
        RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Phi]"}]]}], ",", "     ", 
      SubscriptBox["u", "\[Phi]"], "=", 
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Psi]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Theta]"}]]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Theta]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "=", 
      SubscriptBox["u", "\[Theta]"], ",", "        ", 
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Phi]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "=", 
      FractionBox[
       SubscriptBox["u", "\[Phi]"], 
       RowBox[{"sin", "\[Theta]"}]]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"fb090e42-4a91-4fb1-ae22-6ab3a215ea12"],

Cell["22.2  The flow-map gradient and FTLE", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"622dffff-a64f-4145-b6b4-554bc0d71847"],

Cell["\<\
Seed a uniform grid of tracers, advect for time T under the (snapshot) field, \
and form the flow-map (deformation) gradient F by finite-differencing \
neighbouring tracers, carrying the sphere metric (arc-lengths d\[Theta] and \
sin\[Theta]\[ThinSpace]d\[Phi]). With \[Sigma]_max the largest singular value \
of F (equivalently \[Sqrt]\[Lambda]_max of the right Cauchy\[Dash]Green \
tensor C=\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(F\), \(T\)]\)F), the FTLE is\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8834c9ed-6110-4fac-b980-38705405d23a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "FTLE", ""], 
   RowBox[{"(", "x", ")"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["1", 
     RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", "T", "\[RightBracketingBar]"}]], 
    RowBox[{"ln", " ", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "max", ""], 
     RowBox[{"(", "x", ")"}]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"96821349-25a0-4447-ad36-c03ee7c6196f"],

Cell["\<\
Ridges of \[Sigma]_FTLE are the finite-time transport barriers \[Dash] and on \
a jet-bearing flow they trace the jet cores directly, a dynamical diagnostic \
no single vorticity snapshot provides.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3a6fd9dd-bbd7-431d-9a5a-b19df08d95cd"],

Cell["\<\
References: Haller (2015) Annu. Rev. Fluid Mech. 47, 137 (LCS review); \
Shadden, Lekien & Marsden (2005) Physica D 212, 271 (FTLE ridges as LCS).\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"29f369f6-3fae-4aaf-9649-ad5d51997b46"],

Cell["\<\
23.  Honest Interior: the True (r/R)^l Evanescent Continuation\
\>", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"6edfad71-9466-4049-bc24-70c2d4a84c06"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #20 (honest_interior.py). The v6 renderer continued the surface \
field inward with a mixing-length-scaled factor (r/R)\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\()\
\), \((l/L_ref)\)]\) using L_ref=10, and painted the inner core ~32\[Times] \
amplified. Both OVERSTATE what a 2-D barotropic field can say about the deep \
interior. The mathematically honest continuation of a degree-l surface \
pattern that is regular at the origin is the interior solution of Laplace's \
equation:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7d3582b8-7fb1-4c34-9b5a-1fb895a3a54a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[CapitalPhi]", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"r", ",", "\[Theta]", ",", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", "lm", ""], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      FractionBox["r", "R"], ")"}], "l"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "lm", ""], 
    RowBox[{"Y", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"\[Theta]", ",", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}]}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"773d6723-762a-4c13-975f-d5b61ee3a0c0"],

Cell["\<\
\[Dash] NOT solved interior dynamics. It is EVANESCENT: high-l (small-scale) \
structure decays within a thin skin of depth ~R/l, while only the largest \
scales reach the base. The l/L_ref exponent with L_ref=10 inflates the \
e-folding depth by ~10\[Times]. For the forcing-scale modes (l\[TildeTilde]60\
\[Dash]80) the honest factor at the base r=0.71R is\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8f6852a2-79cb-4b9e-9218-5e09d578026a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"(", "0.71", ")"}], "l"], "\[TildeTilde]", 
   RowBox[{"4", "\[Times]", 
    SuperscriptBox["10", 
     RowBox[{"-", "11"}]]}], "     ", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"l", "\[TildeTilde]", "60", "\[Dash]", "80"}], ")"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"01a3343d-971b-407c-b40e-a2352d1836f1"],

Cell["\<\
i.e. the interior is essentially EMPTY. That is the correct answer: a 2-D \
barotropic model carries NO radial information, so any visible interior \
structure is decoration, not physics. The module therefore offers the honest \
alternatives named in the spec: (a) show ONLY the 2-D surface field, no \
interior; or (b) render the TRUE (r/R)^l continuation (surface-confined for \
forcing-scale modes). A genuine 3-D field requires items #15\[Dash]#17.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"77f8148b-9342-46d6-900e-2a5201416a4b"],

Cell["\<\
References: project audits physics_audit.md and v6_critical_audit.md \
\[Section]\[Section]4.4, 5.1; for a genuine 3-D field see \
\[Section]\[Section]15\[Dash]17.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"bb57e16b-a68a-4cfd-b166-ceb46c808037"],

Cell["24.  Summary: From 2-D Turbulence Toward Solar Convection", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"56c77419-cf88-489d-b8ec-ec3ea802ee25"],

Cell["\<\
The twenty improvements trace a deliberate arc. Tier A (\[Section]\[Section]9\
\[Dash]13) makes the barotropic model demonstrably do what it claimed: a wide \
forcing\[Dash]Rhines separation and controlled injection aimed at the \
zonostrophic regime, 2nd-/4th-order time stepping with exact linear \
treatment, a clean spectral sink, and \[Dash] decisively \[Dash] a direct \
FLUX measurement that distinguishes a real dual cascade from a merely \
broadened spectrum. Tier B (\[Section]\[Section]14\[Dash]17) adds genuine new \
physics: a self-consistent mean flow, topographic locking, a finite \
deformation radius, self-consistent baroclinic jets, gravity waves, and the \
solar-relevant Lorentz force. Tier C (\[Section]\[Section]18\[Dash]21) \
crosses the line into ACTUAL convection \[Dash] buoyancy, an energy equation, \
a radial dimension, correct anelastic stratification, and a real solar \
background. Tier D (\[Section]\[Section]22\[Dash]23) converts the output from \
illustration into evidence and removes the one remaining misleading element.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fd902178-9cb4-40ae-aa1c-2bb727befc57"],

Cell["\<\
The honest through-line: the numerics of the base solver are verified \
correct; the gaps were always physical SCOPE and run DISCIPLINE, not bugs. \
The single cheapest change with the largest scientific payoff remains items \
1+2+8 together \[Dash] run long enough, with wider scale separation, and \
MEASURE THE FLUX \[Dash] which alone lets the project make a defensible claim \
about jets. Everything from \[Section]18 onward is the honest destination if \
\"solar convection\" is to be more than a motivating label.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d240ce38-77ed-410c-bcb3-17cf40fff198"],

Cell["References", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"d1ccdba1-44ad-4d65-837c-53c1d8568080"],

Cell["\<\
Busse, F. H. (1970). Thermal instabilities in rapidly rotating systems. \
Journal of Fluid Mechanics, 44, 441\[Dash]460. [Columnar/banana-cell \
convection.]\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fbeb74b7-8641-45e1-a65b-d8d3aa660164"],

Cell["\<\
Gilman, P. A. (1975). Linear simulations of Boussinesq convection in a deep \
rotating spherical shell. Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences, 32, \
1331\[Dash]1352.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6101f1db-ad18-49d2-9d5c-0ea962d29fa4"],

Cell["\<\
Brun, A. S. & Toomre, J. (2002). Turbulent convection under the influence of \
rotation: sustaining a strong differential rotation. The Astrophysical \
Journal, 570, 865\[Dash]885. [The ASH code.]\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2aacdad8-41ec-48c2-9a3b-6d506bd82353"],

Cell["\<\
Miesch, M. S. (2005). Large-scale dynamics of the convection zone and \
tachocline. Living Reviews in Solar Physics, 2, 1. [Comprehensive review.]\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6ad70943-9b36-4232-af17-b201921b314e"],

Cell["\<\
Jones, C. A. (2011). Planetary magnetic fields and fluid dynamos. Annual \
Review of Fluid Mechanics, 43, 583\[Dash]614. [Rotating convection and the \
Taylor\[Dash]Proudman constraint.]\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"342224f7-90d3-4381-8d7c-d02c7b51147c"],

Cell["\<\
Featherstone, N. A. & Hindman, B. W. (2016). The spectral amplitude of \
stellar convection and its scaling in the high-Rayleigh-number regime. The \
Astrophysical Journal, 818, 32. [The Rayleigh code.]\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d8633638-51c0-473a-979c-69b76e2ce5b2"],

Cell["\<\
Vallis, G. K. (2017). Atmospheric and Oceanic Fluid Dynamics, 2nd ed. \
Cambridge University Press. [Barotropic vorticity equation, geostrophic \
turbulence, Taylor\[Dash]Proudman theorem.]\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7b7a5838-b878-4f5e-bcfd-247f9e3e2b37"],

Cell["\<\
Rhines, P. B. (1975). Waves and turbulence on a beta-plane. Journal of Fluid \
Mechanics, 69, 417\[Dash]443. [The Rhines scale and the arrest of the inverse \
cascade into zonal jets.]\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c0ffee00-0009-4000-8000-000000000001"],

Cell["\<\
Charney, J. G., Fj\[OSlash]rtoft, R. & von Neumann, J. (1950). Numerical \
integration of the barotropic vorticity equation. Tellus, 2, 237\[Dash]254. \
[The original barotropic-vorticity computation.]\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e5f57e98-9119-4c00-804f-4941988ae7aa"],

Cell["", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"09ea3dc4-deb7-4975-ab28-291647be16f4"],

